<HEADLINE> Russia Warns Against Force in Solving Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Igor Ivanov, Russian first deputy
foreign minister, warned Saturday that any attempt to solve the
Kosovo issue by force might trigger even more bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
Russia would reject any attempt to exercise force or to impose
economic sanctions, the minister, who is in charge of European
affairs, said in an interview with the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
Russia appealed to all sides involved for extreme caution
because any wrong step might seriously harm Europe's stability,
said Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that constructive pressure must be exerted to bring
the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, an autonomous province of
Yugoslavia, and Yugoslav leaders to the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
However, the international community should not be directly
involved in the process of talks, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
There was no reason to lift the arms embargo against Yugoslavia
yet since the situation in Kosovo had not seen any active change,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
