<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Education Ministry Under Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 9 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean female minister
Saturday criticized the new policy in the education ministry to
allow pregnant students and teachers to continue with training.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State in the vice-president's office Tsungirirayi
Hungwe said she did not agree with the circular sent out by the
ministry this year.
</P>
<P>
The circular authorized female students to continue with their
training even if they became pregnant in the duration of their
courses.
</P>
<P>
''I believe we should do one thing at a time. There is no way
one can be a student and a mother at the same time,'' she said as
she officiated at the graduation ceremony for over 400 students
at Mutare Teachers College in east Zimbabwe, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
She cautioned female trainee teachers to refrain from falling
pregnant while still at college saying this would adversely
affect their performance during their training.
</P>
<P>
She also lashed out at teachers who indulged in sexual
relationships with pupils and said such teachers had no place in
the profession.
</P>
<P>
''This, in my view, is the worst offense a teacher can commit
in the profession,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
