<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G8 Ministers Launch Action Program on Forests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from the Group of
Eight countries launched an action program on forests here
Saturday, setting out specific measures to support substantial
sustainable forest management worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued at the end of the G8 foreign ministers
conference, said that this program is a practical response to the
continuing destruction and degradation of the world's forests.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged all G8 countries to monitor and assess the
state of their own forests using agreed national level criteria
and indicators for sustainable forest management.
</P>
<P>
The other measures, set out in the action program, are as
follows: developing national forest programs, classifying protected
areas, enhancing the contribution of the private sector to sustain
forestry management and addressing illegal logging.
</P>
<P>
The statement also stressed that the action program is an
excellent example of how cooperation between G8 countries can
produce concrete and action-oriented solution to global problems.
</P>
<P>
The G8 countries are the United States, Britain, Germany,
France, Italy, Canada, Japan and Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
