<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Veterans Demand More Benefits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Despite almost five billion
Zimbabwean Dollars (about 300 million U.S. Dollars) awarded in
monthly pensions, Zimbabwean war veterans Saturday used their
national congress as a forum to demand more benefits.
</P>
<P>
Addressing over 800 delegates to the Third Congress of
Zimbabwe National Liberation War Veterans Association, Chenjerai
Hunzvi, chairman of the association said that the former
fighters' demands had not been fully met.
</P>
<P>
Affirmative action was needed for the ex-combatants in areas
such as housing, education, health and business, Hunzvi told the
congress held in Umzingwane District of west Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"The acute shortage of housing for ex-combatants is well
known. Since the ministry concerned with housing is now one with
local government, we expect affirmative action toward allocation
of housing stands to our members throughout the country," the
Zimbabwe News Agency quoted Hunzvi as saying.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the veteran association complained that
although many of them desire to start income generating projects
in various parts of the country, there has not been much
affirmative action from local authorities in allocation.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government, through its department of war
veterans' affairs, should implement the provisions of the war
veterans' act, and schemes on projects in health and education
should be concretized, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hunzvi urged the department to recruit personnel for its
provincial offices through the association while its members are
demanding that they should be allowed to select the minister to
run the department.
</P>
<P>
Now, there are over 50,000 former fighters registered in the
country. They held demonstrations last year demanding more
benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
