<HEADLINE> Pakistan Exports Wheat to Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has officially begun
exporting wheat to neighboring Afghanistan, and the first
consignment of 10,000 tons of wheat has already been despatched to
that country.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by Minister for Food and Agriculture Abdus
Sattar Lalika Saturday in Peshawar, capital of the North West
Frontier Province, at the inauguration ceremony of wheat
despatches to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed by the two countries last year,
Pakistan will export a total of 600,000 tons of wheat to
Afghanistan per annum.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government wanted to promote trade with
neighboring countries, said Lalika, adding that "It is our moral
obligation to enhance trade relations with the war-torn country of
Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
He said that trade between Pakistan and Afghanistan would
benefit the people of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the opening of legal export of wheat to Afghanistan
would also put an end to the menace of smuggling of wheat and
flour to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and Afghanistan possess tremendous potential of
boosting bilateral trade, said Lalika. The trade potential of the
two countries needs exploitation to the maximum level and for this
purpose the Pakistani government was evolving a transparent
mechanism for bilateral trade, the Minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
