<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Promise for Veterans to Be Honored: Mugabe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Saturday assured war veterans that the government is seeking ways
through which the ex-fighters can be awarded all their benefits
as promised in the war veterans act.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said this in a written speech read on his behalf at the
opening of the Third Congress of Zimbabwe National Liberation War
Veterans Association by minister of state responsible for war
veterans affairs Witness Mangwende.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, patron of the veterans association, was unable to
attend the congress as he is at present in Cairo, Egypt, for the
G-15 summit.
</P>
<P>
The outstanding benefits for war veterans who have each
received a lump sum of 50,000 Zimbabwean Dollars (about 3,000
U.S. Dollars) in gratitude and are getting a monthly pension of
2,000 Zimbabwean Dollars (117 U.S. Dollars) include free
education, medical care, funeral expenses and loan benefit
schemes.
</P>
<P>
"While the government is taking all measures to reduce the
expenditure, it is only fair that those who brought about our
independence should be given serious consideration," the Zimbabwe
News Agency quoted the president as saying in his speech.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe also commended the association for forming the Zimbabwe
Ex-combatants Foundation Investment Fund, saying their collective
approach proved that they had organized themselves as a
formidable force for economic empowerment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, chairman of the veterans association Chenjerai
Hunzvi said the former fighters' demands have not been fully met.
They demand more benefits such as housing, education, health and
business.
</P>
<P>
There are over 50,000 former fighters registered in the
country. In the past year, they held demonstrations demanding
more benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
