<HEADLINE> Former U.S. Attorney-General Criticizes Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Former United States
Attorney-General Ramsey Clark Saturday blamed the United
Nations-imposed economic sanction on Iraq for causing sufferings
to the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here, Clark described the sanction
as "an act of genocide against the Iraqi people," asserting that
its continuation contravenes the international norms and treaties.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "the time is ripe" to lift the "unjust"
sanction in an effort to end the sufferings of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed the embargo on Iraq in 1990
after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Clark, who heads an 82-member U.S. humanitarian and human
rights delegation, arrived here Friday evening. His delegation,
the largest U.S. delegation visiting Iraq ever since the 1991
Gulf War, sent Iraq 4 million U.S. dollars worth of medicine and
medical appliances donated by Americans.
</P>
<P>
Clark said that hundreds of thousands of Americans, including
those with Islamic centers and churches, have been joining efforts
to collect medicine from all over the U.S. for the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
He praised highly the activities of humanitarian organizations,
churches and Islamic centers aimed at ending the "unjust" sanction
on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Clark opposed the U.S.-led Gulf War, which kicked the Iraqi
troops out of Kuwait. He has visited Baghdad several times after
the war and met with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein every time.
</P>
</TEXT>
