<HEADLINE> GCC Higher Committee to Discuss Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 9 (Xinhua) -- The Higher Committee of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) will start a two-day meeting in Doha,
Qatar, Sunday to discuss military cooperation among the six member
states.
</P>
<P>
The committee assigned to implement joint defense decisions and
military cooperation among the states will discuss issues
concerning the force of the Peninsula Shield and the
implementation of the communication and cooperation network among
them, the GCC Secretariat said in a statement in Riyadh, Saudi
Arabia, Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 8,000-strong Peninsula Desert Shield force is a GCC joint
armed force based in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Major General Faleh Abdallah Al-Shatti, GCC Assistant
Secretary General for Military Affairs, has said that the force is
now ready to rush to the help of any member country that is
threatened.
</P>
<P>
A GCC plan to raise the Peninsula Shield troops from 8,000 to
25,000 and to establish a joint early warning system has been
carried out since last year.
</P>
<P>
As to the integrated network to link up the commands of the
six Gulf states, Al-Shatti said last week that the execution of
the network would start in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
He said the network, which costs over 150 million U.S. dollars,
was designed to facilitate communication among supreme commands of
the GCC states.
</P>
<P>
The GCC which was founded in 1982 as a regional political,
economic and military body, groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the
United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Bahrain and Oman.
</P>
<P>
The member countries' final aim is to strengthen the
capability of the joint forces that requires purchase of new
compatible radar, missiles and automated communications, command
and control air defense systems.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shatti said the member states have agreed to increase the
number of troops and acquiring highly-advanced weapons, adding
that a new camp for this force would be built in Hafr El-Batin,
northwest of Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
