<HEADLINE> WB to Help Angola Remove Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 9 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will offer Angola
five million U.S. Dollars in demining and reconstruction, Angolan
Minister of Social Relief and resettlement Albino Malungo has
said.
</P>
<P>
Malungo left for the United States on Friday night to discuss
with the World Bank officials about the final details of the aid,
the Angolan News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The assistance provided by the World Bank will help remove the
mines across the war-ravaged country, said the Angolan minister.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the Angolan government will receive 20 million U.S.
Dollars donated by 20 U.S. entrepreneurs, part of which will be
used in the reconstruction of war-damaged cities, like Catabola
and Camacupa in the central Bie Province and Cazombo in the
southeastern Moxico Province.
</P>
<P>
These U.S. business leaders paid a visit to Angola last week
to assess the situation of the mines scattered in the country and
the progress of the demining process so that they could provide
aid needed to help get rid of all the mines by 2010.
</P>
<P>
During his seven-day visit to the U.S., Malungo will meet with
the U.S. Senators and entrepreneurs who initiated the campaign
for clearing lethal mines in the world and attend a supper in
honor of 300 advocates for demining from countries on earth.
</P>
<P>
Angola is among the countries hardest hit by mines, with about
11 million laid in nearly 30 years of anti-colonialist war and
the civil war, according to the statistics released by the
related department of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
So far, up to 70,000 people have been wounded by mines planted
in the fields and along the roads in Angola, which pose great
threat to people's life and production. And from time to time,
there are reports about casualties in mine explosions in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
