<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Officials Urged to Fight Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye has urged government leaders to play an
exemplary role in the country's anti-corruption war.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting of executives from various regions of the
Tanzanian mainland Friday, Sumaye warned that the war against
corruption will not be successful unless the government leaders
are fully committed to the drive.
</P>
<P>
He ordered every regional and district commissioner to keep
his or her office clean, warning that the government will leave
no stones unturned to punish those corrupt elements.
</P>
<P>
"Go back and strive to ensure that all loopholes of corruption
are stemmed," he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the regional and district commissioners to behave
themselves and be strict with their subordinates so that the
latter can adhere to the laid down regulations and be responsible
for their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye also lashed out at some civil servants who drink liquor
during office hours. "If the nation would not respect work
discipline, the task of reviving economy would not be realized,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister acknowledged that corruption has yet to be
uprooted and still runs rampant among leaders despite the fact
that the government has made efforts to eradicate the vice.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on adverse effects of the El Nino rains, he urged
every regional and district commissioner to use all resources
available to restore the damaged facilities and services and go
all out to solve the food shortage problem.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the who have gained a lot from the rains
brought by El Nino sell part of their healthy livestocks so that
they will be able to buy food. 
</P>
