<HEADLINE> U.S. Launches Stamp to Fund Breast Cancer Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Postal Service launched on
Saturday the country's first stamp supporting the breast cancer
research program.
</P>
<P>
The 40-cent stamp will be deemed valid for postage at the
prevailing First-Class rate, currently 32 cents, with its net
proceeds above the cost of postage earmarked for research
organizations, the Service said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The move abides by a 1997 U.S. legislation which directed the
Postal Service to issue a semipostal stamp valid for postage,
costing an additional amount above the First-Class rate, not to
exceed 25 percent, and allowing for the recovery of reasonable
costs associated with the stamp.
</P>
<P>
The stamp will be issued nationwide in August in preparation
for the National Breast Cancer Awareness Month in October.
</P>
<P>
Breast cancer is considered the most commonly diagnosed cancer
among women in every major ethic group in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Experts say when breast cancer is diagnosed in stages I and II,
five-year survival rates are nearly 95 percent and there are
better options for breast-conserving surgery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
