<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Kills 50 Civilians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 9 (Xinhua) -- The remnants of the junta forces and
rebel allies have killed at least 50 people in northern Sierra
Leone in a fresh round of persecution of civilians.
</P>
<P>
The junta remnants and rebels, who were driven out of the
capital Freetown in mid-February, Friday also burnt down several
others in villages some 70 miles from Makeni, a major town in the
north of the war-ravaged country, according to a British
Broadcasting Corporation report monitored here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a local priest as saying that the people in
that area were persecuted because they firmly supported President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, who was reinstated in March after the fall of
the junta.
</P>
<P>
The remnants of the junta forces and their rebel allies then
retreated to the northern and eastern parts of the country, where
the west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) has been carrying
our an operation to mop up them.
</P>
<P>
The terrorist activities of the junta forces at the border
areas have forced some 160,000 local residents to flee to
neighboring Guinea since March.
</P>
<P>
However, a commander of the Revolutionary United Front (RUF),
the rebel group which became allied to the junta shortly after
the ousting of Kabbah's government last May, denied the accused
killings, saying it was "complete propaganda."
</P>
<P>
The RUF commander also accused the Guinean intelligence of
acting against his armed group.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Guineans are working together with
ECOMOG and the Sierra Leonean civil defense group Kamajors to
fight his group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
