<HEADLINE> Iran Encourages More Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 9 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian official Saturday
assured a 40-member French business delegation of Iran's
preferential policies for foreign investment, expecting more
foreign capitals to be injected into the country's ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of Iran's High Council of the Free Trade Zones
Morteza Alviri told the French delegation that foreign banks are
allowed to do business in the Iranian free trade zones and to
exchange foreign currency at floating rate being traded at free
market, according to the Iranian official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
The foreign investors doing business in the Iranian free trade
zones will enjoy a 15-year tax exemption and they are allowed to
transfer their capital and interests abroad with no limitation,
said Alviri, also presidential advisor on financial affairs.
</P>
<P>
He noted that foreign companies involved in business and
industry in the Iranian free trade zones will find lucrative
opportunities on the Iranian market and a market of 300 million
population in the Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
The French delegation, comprising representatives from 30
French companies, arrived here on Saturday on a four-day visit,
the first of its kind since 1991, to check the opportunity for
business cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Headed by former chief of the French National Center for
Employers Francois Perigot, the delegation came to Iran as the
United States is discussing whether to punish the French oil
company TOTAL, which in last September concluded a big deal of
2 billion U.S. dollars to develop an Iranian offshore gas field.
</P>
<P>
Washington has threatened to impose economic sanctions on TOTAL
and several other foreign companies for violating its 1996
Iran-Libya Sanction Act, a law which bans any investment of more
than 40 million dollars in Iran's energy sector by any foreign
company.
</P>
<P>
Due to the U.S. efforts to isolate Tehran and insecurity for
foreign investment in the country, Iran only attracted some 782
million dollars during the past two years, an Iranian official
announced last December.
</P>
<P>
However, more and more foreign economic delegations are coming
to Iran to seek opportunities for cooperation, after the moderate
President Mohammad Khatami came to power in last August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
