<HEADLINE> Mbeki Urges Upliftment of Poor, Unemployed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 9 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy President
Thabo Mbeki Saturday called on leaders of all departments to help
eliminate a national emergency caused by the legacy of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
Apartheid had left South Africa with a social disaster of immense
proportions, represented by the poor, starving and unemployed, Mbeki
said at an installation banquet of University of Durban-Westville
Vice-Chancellor Mapule Ramashala.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki also attributed increasing victims of HIV/AIDS, rape and
physical abuse to the old and bad social system.
</P>
<P>
"This emergency impacts negatively on all of us and remains
the one factor which threatens the realization of the national
goal of a peaceful and prosperous society," Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
The apartheid state had poured resources into its racist
project of the upliftment of, at best, 15 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
The democratic state had an obligation to spread virtually the
same volume of resource among 100 percent of the population, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Yet the expectation persists that the government will somehow
find it within its power rapidly to bridge the yawning gulf
between black and white by raising the standard of living of the
former to equal that attained by the latter, and that in a short
period of time," Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
There could be no doubt about the need to devote more
resources to the task of redressing apartheid imbalances, the
deputy president added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
