<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Saudi Arabia Saturday broke ground for the
construction of the second largest dam in the Middle East after
the High Dam of Aswan in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The dam, named after Saudi King Fahd, is built in the southern
province of Bisha. It's cost is estimated at 65.6 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The dam with a height of 103 meters and width of 507 meters
can reserve up to 325 million cubic meters of water.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Moroccan privatization drive has generated 2 billion
dollars through selling 52 of the total 114 state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The selling value is 1.4 billion dollars and businessmen have
invested 600 million dollars in the enterprises.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- According to the Organization of Arab Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OAPEC), by early 1997, the proven oil
reserves of the Arab countries amounted to 643 billion barrels in
the eastern Arab region and 59 billion barrels in north Africa.
</P>
<P>
This accounts for 62 percent of the world oil reserves standing
at 1,036 billion barrels in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Total investments in the oil sector in the Arab world from 1998
to 2003 are expected to reach 90 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's trade volume with the other 15 member states
of the Group-15 stood at 1079.8 million dollars during 1996-97
against 770.2 million dollars in 1995 and 471.3 million in 1994.
</P>
