<HEADLINE> FAA Orders Immediate Inspections of Boeing 737s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Aviation
Administration (FAA) on Sunday extended its earlier order for
additional older Boeing 737s to be immediately inspected for
possible fuel pump damage.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's order broadens the inspections to include Boeing
737-300, 400 and 500 series planes. The new order will affect
additional 118 domestic planes and 282 worldwide.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the agency ordered inspections of some 152 Boeing
737-100 and 200 planes after mechanics working on a Continental
Airlines Boeing 737-200 found fuel leaking out of a pipe running
through one of the plane's wing fuel tanks.
</P>
<P>
The agency ordered operators of the planes to inspect two sets
of fuel pump electrical lines in each wing within seven days or
five flight hours.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's order was made after the wiring in a United Airlines
737, inspected after the initial order, showed clear signs of
arching in one location and a second spot where bare wire was
exposed, the FAA said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
It said operators have completed inspections of only 13 of the
affected aircrafts and found signs of wear on the insulation of
wires in half of the 26 main pump lines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
