<HEADLINE> Nepali PM Committed to Free Elections in Next April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister and Nepali
Congress President Girija Prasad Koirala said Sunday in Biratnagar
of eastern Nepal that he is committed to holding free and fair
general elections in April-May, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Koirala, who was in eastern Nepal for various programs,
stressed at a press meet the need to ensure the participation of
not only the political parties and the parties represented in
parliament, but also the people in general including the ethnic
groups, indigenous people and the downtrodden so as to make their
roles meaningful.
</P>
<P>
The official RSS news agency quoted him as saying that national
consensus is the only weapon for putting an end to the existing
anomalies and aberrations.
</P>
<P>
Koirala's minority government, which took office on April 15,
is the fifth government in the country since the mid-term polls in
November 1994.
</P>
<P>
He said on Saturday that since minority government is by nature
not guaranteed of a long-term survival, another party could be
included for a majority government.
</P>
<P>
He said he would prefer the main opposition Communist Party of
Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) to its breakaway faction
the Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML). 
</P>
