<HEADLINE> Costa Wins German Open as Rival Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Albert Costa won the German Open as
opponent fellow Spaniard Alex Corretja retired in the third set in
Hamburg on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This was Costa's first tournament since claiming the Marbella
title last September.
</P>
<P>
Unseeded Costa led 6-2, 6-0, 1-0 when Corretja retired from
fatigue. Fourth-seeded Corretja was stretched to three sets in
every round in the Open.
</P>
<P>
Costa won his first two service games to love and held break
point in the second game when Corretja double-faulted. Although
Corretja was able to recover a Costa break for 3-1, he was able to
offer little resistance after that.
</P>
<P>
Costa broke again to lead 4-2 and again for the set, and then
dropped just one point in the first three games of the second set.
</P>
<P>
Costa was aware before the match of Corretja's problem.
</P>
<P>
"We are friends and spoke before the match and he told me he
had no power," said Costa. "He played one day six sets, and then
three sets in two more matches. It's too much."
</P>
<P>
Corretja's retirement marked the third time in three days that
players failed to last the distance here.
</P>
<P>
Goran Ivanisevic quit in the second set of his quarter-final
against Mantilla, and Karol Kucera conceded his semi-final against
Costa because of blisters. 
</P>
