<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Hospitals Alert As Blood Stocks Fall to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Some British hospitals have been
told to restrict their blood transfusion orders only to identified
patients, as national blood stocks fell to the lowest levels yet
this year.
</P>
<P>
The National Blood Authority, which collects blood supplies,
has written to hospitals in London and the Southeast last week,
saying that the supplies of group O blood has fallen to
dangerously low limits, the Sunday Telegraph revealed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper reported that despite a nationwide appeal for
more donors, blood stocks were already low at 14,270 units last
Tuesday, then fell to 12,300 units and had only marginally climbed
to 13,341 units by last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The accepted "safe" recommended level for blood stocks is
15,000 units.
</P>
<P>
The National Blood Authority has warned that unless there is an
improvement in blood supplies, operations will start to be
cancelled from this week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
