<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jones Ready to Sprint Ahead in Fastest Women Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, China, May 10 (Xinhua) -- World champion Marion Jones,
who clocked the year best of 10.79 seconds at the IAAF Osaka Grand
Prix on Saturday, said today that she has been ready to defend her
honor as the world 100-meter queen at the worlds' fastest woman
100-meter race to be held here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
After boarding on the plane from Bejing, Jones said that she
was in a superb form and ready to show her talent on the Chinese
soil.
</P>
<P>
"I feel great and I'm ready to run," said the 22-year-old, who
declined to take any drink and refreshments offered by the
stewardess.
</P>
<P>
"Is there a McDonard's in Chengdu," asked the American who
caught the plane at the last minute with boyfriend C. J Henter,
coach Trevor Graham and Chandra Sturrup of Bahamas, the 1996
Olympic 100m fourth finisher who will also compete in the fastest
women sprint.
</P>
<P>
But the world champion then kept her lips tight for any details.
</P>
<P>
The versatile sprinter who turned to track from basketball in
1996, has made unbelievable progresses over the past two years.
</P>
<P>
After failing to qualify for the 1996 Atlanta Olympic Games in
the U.S. trials, she emerged to win the 100m title at last year's
World Champinships in 10.76 seconds, and was timed at 6.95 seconds
in the 60m two months ago, the year's world best.
</P>
<P>
"She is sure to break the world record. But not now, it is not
the right time," said her coach Graham, adding that it will not be
difficult to register a time of 10.60 for her protegee on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Graham said that there was no secret behind Jones' remarkable
progress, saying "there is no secret. I just try to do my work to
keep her running fast. Just try out the points basically."
</P>
<P>
"But, we are confident, we are here to win. We have been ready
for the race because there are so many world's top sprinters here."
</P>
<P>
However, Graham, who has been Jones' coach for just one year,
admitted that they paid no special attention to the race although
it was believed to be one of the highlights in the 1998 athletics
calender.
</P>
<P>
"We just treat it as an ordinary race during the season," he
said, indicating it was no different from the Grand Prix in Japan
and Europe.
</P>
<P>
But Li Xuemei, the Chinese top challenger for Jones, who
surprised the world with a 10.79 run, the second fastest time in
the world last season to Jones' 10.76, has directed all her
efforts towards the race.
</P>
<P>
To focus on the high profile competition in her hometown, she
has skipped several indoor races as well as meetings in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"I think I'm still in a good shape," said the 24-year-old Li,
who trained about one hour Sunday morning and was rumored to have
been dogged by a right knee injury.
</P>
<P>
Li's coach Zhang Rongwei said that "I think she has the calibre
to run a time around 11 seconds."
</P>
<P>
The other world class foreign sprinters due to compete are
Savatheda Fynes of Bahamas, last year's world bronze medalist,
Carlette Guidry, a member of the U.S. 4x100m relay winning team at
the 1996 Olympic with a 10.94 personal best.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Gail Devers and Zhanna Pintussevich of
Ukraine, world 100m silver medalist last year, were expected to
travel to China but withdraw from the race in the last moments.
</P>
<P>
"We want to race against them, but they failed to show up,"
said Graham.
</P>
<P>
The race will start at 16:20 local time after the exhibition
events including the men's and women's sprint hurdles and 400
meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
