<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Shuttlers Arrive in HK for Thomas, Uber Cups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 10 (Xinhua) -- The national team of badminton
world power China arrived in Hong Kong on Sunday to participate in
the Thomas Cup and Uber Cup world badminton team championships
slated here for May 15-25.
</P>
<P>
As the organizers had failed to find sponsorship for the event,
this would be the first ever world-class tournament to be held in
Hong Kong without corporate funding. But the organizers had
repeatedly confirmed that the tournament would go ahead and would
be successful as the previous tournaments.
</P>
<P>
Of the 19 Thomas Cup tournaments held between 1948 to 1996,
Indonesia has won 10 times, followed by Malaysia five times and
China, four times.
</P>
<P>
Li Mao, China's head coach for the men's singles event, had
said that his goal in Hong Kong was to reach the final. He had
predicted that it was very optimistic for his team to reach the
top four. China had not qualified for the tournament finals since
1992.
</P>
<P>
And in the 16 Uber Cup tournaments held since 1956, China and
Japan each has won five times and Indonesia three times. The
Chinese women's team had won the title for five consecutive times
since 1984 before losing the last two tournaments, in 1994 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
But former world champion Li Lingwei, who is now the head coach
for the team's women's singles event, said her team was confident
but she declined to predict a sure victory.
</P>
<P>
Although five of her players are now ranked among the world's
top 10, Li was not so sure what would happen in the Hong Kong
tournament.
</P>
<P>
"The higher world rankings of our players do not necessarily
mean everything we need for the victory," she said in an earlier
interview with Xinhua. "Every medal has to be won through hard
efforts," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
