<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OIC to Launch Efforts to Resume Afghan Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 10 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Islamic
Conference (OIC) will launch fresh efforts to resume the Afghan
peace talks which collapsed here on May 3.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Secretary General of the OIC Ibrahim Saleh Bakar is
expected to arrive here in a couple of days to initiate new
efforts to resume the talks, a report by the News Network
International quoted OIC sources as saying Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in the region, Bakar will visit Afghanistan's
southern city of Kandahar, where he will meet Maulana Abdul Jalil,
a senior official of the Taliban militia for "foreign affairs,"
and is likely to hold a meeting with Mulla Muhammad Rabbani, the
head of the Taliban Interim Council.
</P>
<P>
Bakar will also meet leaders of the rival Northern Alliance and
try to convince them to resume the talks, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he will meet acting Chief of the U.N. Peace Mission
for Afghanistan based in Islamabad James Ngobi, and discuss with
him ways and means to resume the peace talks, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The first ever face-to-face talks between the Taliban militia
and the Northern Alliance held here on April 26 and broke down on
May 3 after the alliance objected to the changes in the Taliban
negotiation delegation.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban team went back to Kandahar on May 1 and failed to
return. A new three-member delegation headed by the
representative of the militia in Islamabad, Abdul Hakim Mujahid,
was assigned the job to represent the Taliban in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Fighting broke out between the Taliban and the forces loyal to
Tajik warlord Ahmed Shah Masood in the north of Kabul soon after
the stalemate in the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
