<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji on Inspectors' Role at Large State Enterprises (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Special inspectors sent by the
central government to watch over the performance and financial
status of key and large state-owned enterprises must be
politically competent and highly principled, just and honest, and
never slacken their self-discipline or pursue personal interests,
according to Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
This remark was made by Zhu on April 28, when the State Council
appointed the first group of 21 special inspectors to large
state-owned enterprises across the country.
</P>
<P>
The 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China set
a goal that the country should help most financially troubled
large- and medium-size state enterprises to overcome their
economic difficulties within three years, and that the
modern-enterprise system should be established in most major state
enterprises by the end of this century, Zhu told the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
"To attain this goal, the Party Central Committee and the State
Council have decided to set up the special inspector system, which
will help enhance the government's supervision on state
enterprises while granting them greater autonomy in management,"
said Zhu.
</P>
<P>
The special inspector system is a major step in China's efforts
to separate government functions from enterprise management, and
is also in conformity with international practices, he said.
</P>
<P>
The main duties of the central inspectors are to conduct
financial supervision of enterprise operations on behalf of the
state and to appraise the performance of principal enterprise
managers in carrying out the Party's principle and policies,
abiding by the country's laws and regulations and running their
businesses, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The inspectors should not get involved in the production or
management of the enterprises," he stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji on Inspectors' Role at Large State Enterprises (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The premier said that only officials ranking above the
vice-minister level are eligible to serve as special inspectors,
and that each inspector will have four special assistants who
should be chosen from officials with professional backgrounds in
banking, finance, personnel, auditing and supervisory bodies, or
macro-control departments.
</P>
<P>
"The five of them shall form a special inspector's office,
which generally will take charge of the supervision of five
enterprises," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu went on to underline the necessity of gradually
establishing a system for the management and supervision of
special inspectors themselves.
</P>
<P>
"We decided that the tenure of office for a special inspector
and his assistants is three years, and that no one will be allowed
to serve a second term in the same enterprise," he said.
</P>
<P>
Any member of the special inspector's office must not hold a
concurrent post in the enterprise, nor can they accept any pay,
benefits, entertainments or gifts from the enterprise, he said.
</P>
<P>
"You are the first group of special inspectors appointed by the
central government of a new term," Zhu said. "I hope all of you
will work hard with a high degree of sense of responsibility and
sense of mission to accomplish this significant task, which will
have a bearing on the overall situation of our country's reforms."
</P>
<P>
Also on April 28, a training class for the 21 special
inspectors and their more than 80 assistants, along with another
class for general accountants from 94 key and large state-owned
enterprises, opened in Zhongnanhai, the central government
compound in downtown Beijing. 
</P>
