<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir Blames Economic Powers for Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohammed has again attacked the world's economic powers for having
a hand in the Asian financial turmoil in an open dialog with
businessmen ahead of the Group-15 summit here Monday.
</P>
<P>
These economic powers sold huge amounts of currencies of
southeast Asian countries, causing their immediate devaluation, by
50 percent in Malaysia and 400 percent in Indonesia, Mahathir told
the businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir arrived here Friday night to attend the G-15 eighth
summit. He discussed with the businessmen the Asian financial
crisis Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
"These powers by doing so have been heading to impoverish the
people of these countries which used to live in prosperity before
the crisis," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
"They have also been aiming to spark off a state of political
chaos, set off economic disturbances and agitate the masses," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, alongside Indonesia, which hit hardest in the
financial crisis, are members of the G-15, now grouping 16
developing countries in Asia, Africa and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis will top the agenda of the three-day
summit, which will also seek ways to reactivate the south-south
cooperation and promote south-north dialog.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said his country has drawn up plans to get out of the
crisis, on top of which is to promote trade with developing
countries, such as Egypt, to minimize reliance on developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
The trade exchange between Malaysia and Egypt in 1996 amounted
to 290 million dollars. The two countries have agreed to up the
volume to 1 billion dollars by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
