<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Calls for More Application of Research Fruits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 10 (Xinhua) -- China is facing an urgent task of
turning more of scientific research findings into industrial
use, said Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing here today.
</P>
<P>
Li, who is also member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China Central
Committee, made the remark when attending a forum to mark the
tenth anniversary of Beijing High and New Technology
Industry Zone, the first of its kind in China.
</P>
<P>
"The experience of the zone over the past decade has
demonstrated that hi-tech zones are an effective means of turning
scientific research results into production forces, which has
yielded remarkable economic and social efficiencies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Set up in 1988, Beijing High and New Technology Industry Zone
has become one of the most successful of its kind in the country,
with 5,650 businesses making electronics,
optic-machinery-electronics, new materials, new energy and energy-
saving, bio-engineering and new medicinal, and environment
protection products.
</P>
<P>
When many countries are adjusting strategies to make development of
high and new technology a forefront of international competition,
the vice premier said, China, as a developing country, should make
development of high and new technology "a most important and
urgent strategic task."
</P>
<P>
To complete the task, Li emphasized that importance should be
attached to basic scientific research and development of applied
technology. Reform on scientific research, education systems must
be deepened to promote the cooperation between industrial
production and research, and training of research and management
personnel should be improved, he said.
</P>
<P>
Li called for more high and new technology enterprises with
high competitive edge be established in high and new technology
development zones.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
