<HEADLINE> German Chemical Businesses Confident in Chinese Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 10 (Xinhua) -- A chemical exhibition to open here
tommorrow has attracted 175 German businesses on the heels of a
successful German consumer goods fair in Shanghai last month.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 exhibitors from 21 countries or regions will
participate in "Achemasia '98," an international show of chemical
technology and the biological industry. More than one-third of the
exhibitors are from Germany.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey indicates that most German enterprises in China
are satisfied with their businesses, despite the impact of the
Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The German Chamber of Industry and Commerce officially opened
its Beijing representative office on April 27, and the next day
more than 800 German business people gathered here for the seventh
Asia-Pacific Conference of German Industry.
</P>
<P>
China's chemical industry is the focus of many German
businesses. China has attracted more than 900 billion U.S. dollars
in direct investment to the area during the past decade.
</P>
<P>
According to Michaela Spaeth, a trade promotion officer with
the German Embassy in China, the investment from German chemical
enterprises in China will triple by 2005. A Sino-German
petrochemical project reportedly has received an investment of 5
billion German marks.
</P>
<P>
"To build Sino-German joint ventures is one kind of
cooperation; Germany would also provide machinery for
China's chemical factories," said Professor Gerhard Kreysa,
president of Dechema, the German Association for Chemical
Apparatus, Technique and Biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
"German manufacturers are confident in the Chinese market,"
Kreysa said.
</P>
<P>
Machinery for the chemical industry will account for 77 percent
of all displayed items in the exhibition, which will be held May
11-16.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will also offer more than 130 seminars on the
latest technology in biology, pharmacy and environmental
protection.  
</P>
</TEXT>
