<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Strengthen Trade Arbitration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Beginning today, disputes
concerning foreign-funded businesses in China will be considered
within the examination scope of the China International Economic
and Trade Arbitration Commission (CIETAC), China's major
commercial arbitration organization.
</P>
<P>
CIETAC's revised responsibilities also include disputes in
financing, the bidding process, engineering construction involving
capital, and technology and service from overseas countries, Hong
Kong, Macao and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Shengchang, CIETAC's deputy director, the
commission has consulted dozens of foreign-funded enterprises each
year for the past few years.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that CIETAC is planning to recruit native
Taiwan arbitrators to enhance its business.
</P>
<P>
About 33 percent of the current cases are disputes between
Chinese shareholders and their overseas partners, including those
from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan. The percentage is increasing,
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The participation of native Taiwan arbitrators would increase
the confidence of Taiwan investors and help protect mutual
investments of the two sides across the Taiwan Straits, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the commission's Shenzhen office recruited native Hong
Kong arbitrators in 1984 with favorable comments from Hong Kong
investors.
</P>
<P>
Wang said Taiwan natives could join CIETAC in their own names,
rather than by the recommendation of government organizations. He
said CIETAC already has received more than 10 applications.
</P>
<P>
The commission has 418 arbitrators sitting on its panel. They
come from 26 countries and regions. There are 137 overseas
arbitrators, including some from the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
CIETAC is China's largest commercial arbitration institution,
receiving 723 cases last year. Since its foundation 40 years ago,
the commission has received more than 6,000 cases involving more
than 10 billion Renminbi. It has been the world leader since 1993
in terms of caseload.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, 17 percent of the cases involved
engineering, real estate, rent, intellectual property rights and
securities. Disputes concerning commodity deals accounted for 45
percent.
</P>
<P>
As commerce develops and the legal system improves, there will
be more conflicts in trade and more people will try to solve them
by means of arbitration, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
