<HEADLINE> MBA Association of Western Returned Scholars Set up in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 10 (Xinhua) -- The MBA Association of the Western
Returned Scholars Association, made up of China's returned MBA
graduates who are now senior executives in China's industrial,
commercial and financial circles, was set up in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
As early as the beginning of the 1980s, the late Chinese leader
Deng Xiaoping reached an agreement with former U.S. President
Ronald Reagan to jointly train high-level business managers.
</P>
<P>
In 1984, the former State Economic and Trade Commission started
an international training program with the United States, Britain
and Europe. So far, a total of 542 master of business
administration degrees have been awarded under the program.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the total number of China's MBA graduates
exceeds 1,000, with 35 percent working in state-owned enterprises
and government organizations. Another 35 percent are employed in
joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
The newly founded association aims to offer services to its
members in academic activities and business exchanges and, at the
same time, acting as a bridge between enterprises and research
institutes and governmental organizations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
