<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Defends Rice Copyright Against US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 10 (Xinhua) -- When talking about jasmine rice,
people will naturally add an attribute "Thai" before it, since it
is well acknowledged that Thailand is the right place where people
can find jasmine rice.
</P>
<P>
However, dark clouds are gathering over the fate of Thai
jasmine rice as a U.S. company recently launched a new kind of
rice, using the name "jasmati" as the trademark.
</P>
<P>
The new jasmati rice sparked an uproar of complaints among Thai
rice farmers and exporters as well as government officials and the
ordinary Thais.
</P>
<P>
Thai rice farmers were angered by the move of the U.S. firm,
known as RiceTec Co., saying it was designed to mislead consumers
into believing that the rice was similar to the famous Thai
fragrant jasmine rice.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging the problem, Thai farmers who grow jasmine rice
in the northeastern provinces of Surin, Maha Sarakham and Buri Ram
also condemned the U.S. firm for violating their natural rights by
trading other grain in the name of their "heritage."
</P>
<P>
Thai lawyers and genetic-conservation groups Saturday urged the
Commerce Ministry to file a complaint with the U.S. government
about RiceTec.
</P>
<P>
Jakkrit Kuanpoth of Sukhothai Thammathirat university's School
of Law said Thai rice-exporters could file a lawsuit against
RiceTec in the U.S. court for violating the U.S. Unfair
Competition Act, which protects products and producers from a
certain geographical area.
</P>
<P>
Jakkrit said that according to the U.S. law, the firm may not
trade its grain as jasmati, because the name is a geographical
indicator that the rice is from Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand could lose its market share for jasmine rice to the
jasmati if we don't do anything. We would like to urge the
Commerce Ministry to take action at government level by lodging
complaints with Washington to examine the issue," the Sunday
Nation newspaper quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, deputy minister of agriculture and
cooperatives Newin Chidchob told the local media that Jasmine rice
is a unique brand of Thailand and that the American company should
recognize the fact.
</P>
<P>
It is unbelievable that a company from the world power should
brazenly exploit the famous brand of a developing country, the
deputy minister said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand exports about 5.3 million tons of rice each year, of
which about 25 percent is fragrant or jasmine rice. The United
States is one of the major markets for Thailand's jasmine rice.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. company retorted in its report that the
jasmati rice has no relationship with Thai jasmine rice but was
derived from a variety called Della that originated in Italy.
</P>
<P>
A RiceTec breeder argued that he considered jasmine rice to be
a term for "any aromatic, sticky rice."
</P>
<P>
But when trading, the U.S. firm contradicted its own
explanation by labeling the grain as the "Texas-grown copy of
jasmine rice from Thailand."
</P>
<P>
Last year, RiceTec sought and was awarded patents on "basmati,"
the Indian aromatic, long grain rice, bringing the firm a monopoly
to market it.
</P>
<P>
Farmers, academics and biologists in India are in the process
of filing a complaint with the World Trade Organization on this
issue.
</P>
<P>
Jakkrit said the U.S. firm had not yet patented jasmati, but
the case of the Indian basmati has prompted concerns among Thai
farmers that they could lose the right to grow what their fathers
had begun to grow.
</P>
<P>
Songkran Chitrakorn, deputy director of the Agriculture
Ministry's Rice Research Institute, said jasmine rice originates
in and is unique to Thailand. The ministry has its record that
Thai farmers have grown the variety for over half a century.
</P>
<P>
An organic rice farmer from Surin province said no one could
claim ownership or monopoly rights in relation to jasmine rice.
</P>
<P>
"Anyone who would steal the rice from Thai farmers is truly
shameless," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anwar: Malaysia Has No Surplus Budget This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will not have a
surplus budget this year because of the current economic problems,
unlike last year when it recorded a 6 billion ringgit (about 1.579
billion U.S. dollars) surplus, Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
For the same reason the country would also not attain high
growth this year and the next, Anwar, who is also finance
minister, said while addressing a forum here.
</P>
<P>
"While we basked in being able to attain a 6-billion ringgit
(about 1.579 billion dollars) surplus last year, we have to admit
that it is impossible to maintain a surplus budget this year," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The government would continue adopting tight fiscal measures in
dealing with the current situation, he said, adding the tight
fiscal policy however would not deny the people of basic
facilities such health, education or limit poverty eradication
programs and in fact efforts towards that end would be
intensified.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would not compromise on providing
facilities to the people, who in his view, were the most
vulnerable to the current economic problems.
</P>
<P>
"If we have the means, we'll use them firstly to ensure the
well-being of as many people as possible," the finance minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar reminded the corporate sector that although the
government's current focus appeared to favor only that sector, it
was actually supporting strategic projects which could serve as
the catalyst to spur national economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
He said: "As such, while we take on the problems together, they
(the corporate sector) should not assume that the government's
responsibility is solely to uphold and defend them at the expense
of priorities for the masses."
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the government's stand on putting the masses first
was clear.
</P>
<P>
"When allocating the recent 1 billion ringgit (about 263.852
million dollars) aid from the International Monetary Fund, we gave
priority to the needs of education, health, small and medium-scale
industries and petty business," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
