<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FEATURE: Surrealistic Missile Base Rises From Gobi Desert (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lanzhou, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Adeptly sliding beads on an abacus,
General Zhao Xi ran calculations for the trial flight of China's
first unmanned plane 30 years ago in a desert laboratory 1,600
kilometers west of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The location is ghastly: in the vast Gobi Desert littered with
the ruins of outposts built 2,000 years ago by Chinese emperors
against the invasion of the Huns.
</P>
<P>
The site could be a dreamland for archeologists or adventurous
tourists. But, it's a secret military base that today is
off-limits to archeologists and tourists alike. The landscape
conceals China's state-of-the-art test site for missiles where
thousands of rockets have been launched.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Xi, a leading scientist, and his colleagues from the base
used abacuses 30 years ago to design and calculate missile tests.
</P>
<P>
But today, tens of thousands of lights on large computers are
flashing as well as sophisticated optical, electronic and laser
instruments.
</P>
<P>
"It has taken the wisdom, youth and hot blood of several
generations of young Chinese scientists to nourish this piece of
wasteland into what it is today," said General Zuo Jizhang, chief
engineer at the site.
</P>
<P>
A stroll on the streets shows that the base looks like an
economic boom town springing up on the legendary Silk Road in
northwest China's Badain Jaran Desert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijingers Mark Mother's Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Although viewed as a western event,
