</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FEATURE: Surrealistic Missile Base Rises From Gobi Desert (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shrouded by trees are supermarkets, schools, hotels, post
offices, banks, bookstores and apartment buildings as well as
research and office buildings.
</P>
<P>
Parked on both sides of the road are military aircraft ranging
from supersonic fighters to bombers and transport planes.
</P>
<P>
Stored inside the silos are missiles ranging from early models
imported decades ago to the latest models developed by Chinese
scientists.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the missile test site started in the summer of
1958, immediately after the late Chairman Mao gave his approval.
</P>
<P>
Since then, pilots from the base have tested nuclear
explosions, satellite launches and a long-range carrier rocket.
</P>
<P>
In 1984 and 1988 the test site went through two technological
renovations which enabled it to test all-dimensional air-to-air
missiles and use digital signals to replace radar signals.
</P>
<P>
In 1994 a research group led by Professor Zhao Xi, chief
designer of the base's target drone, successfully tested a
supersonic pilotless plane which they had designed and
manufactured. China was the second country in the world to have
such a target drone.
</P>
<P>
"The Americans spent eight years and one billion US dollars to
develop such a plane," Zhao said, "but it took us only four years
and less than one million US dollars."
</P>
<P>
Last December, the country's first simulator laboratory for
air-to-air missile testing was built at the base, bringing the
Chinese air force into the digital age.
</P>
<P>
And the chief designer of the lab was a 30-year-old woman,
scientist Li Hong.
</P>
<P>
Li, who began her career studying missile technology at the
base immediately after she graduated from college 10 years ago,
now has a family and a 7-year-old son in the desert.
</P>
<P>
Last year, she took her son to Beijing for sightseeing, but the
boy who grew up in the desert with the missiles was not impressed
by the highrises and neon lights.
</P>
<P>
Uncomfortable with the heavy traffic of the city, her son said,
"Mother, I want to go back home."
</P>
<P>
"I never regret having chosen the desert to write my love to
the motherland," she said. 
</P>
