<HEADLINE> Reigning Champions Defeated in Asian Mountain Bike Races </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Chinese women cyclists swept the
top three positions as both the men's and women's defending
champions failed to retain their respective titles in the Asian
mountain bike championships here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Ma Yanping clocked one hour 43 minutes and 18.345 seconds to
beat compatriot reigning champion Wang Zexiu, winning the 5x5.35
kilometers cross country race in the championships.
</P>
<P>
To achieve her best performance, Ma Yanping established her
upperhands from the very first lap and enjoyed a comfortable edge
of 5 minutes 44.54 seconds against second-placer Wang Zexiu.
</P>
<P>
Yu Quanlan completed the Chinese sweep by finishing third in
one hour 51 minutes and 49.867 seconds.
</P>
<P>
"Although I was recruited into the national team last year, I
was under no pressure to compete in the race," said Ma, adding
that "I am confident of taking the title in the upcoming Asian
Games this December."
</P>
<P>
On her part, Wang Zexiu contributed her fatigue to the busy
schedule as she also competed in other previous meets.
</P>
<P>
In the men's race, Totsui Shunsuke of Japan surged ahead from
the first lap to take the 7x5.35 kilometers title in 2 hours 3
minutes and 30.894 seconds.
</P>
<P>
His compatriot Udagawa Akihito finished second in 2 hours 5
minutes and 41.962 seconds, edging Chinese Li Fuyu to the third
place in 2 hours 10 minutes and 42.683 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Valdez Placido of the Philippines failed to
complete the course together with other 25 competitors as only 16
out of the 42 entries cross the finishing line.
</P>
<P>
As the championships concluded on Sunday, Japan took home two
gold medals from the women's downhill race and the men's cross
country event, while both South Korea and China won one gold medal
apiece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
