<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM to Meet U.N. Chief in Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri is expected to meet United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan in Paris Monday to discuss ways of ending Israeli
occupation in south Lebanon, Lebanon' Orient radio reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Hariri left here Sunday morning for Syria from where
he will head for France.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Damascus, Hariri will hold talks with
Syrian Vice-President Abdul-Halim Khaddam, who is in charge
of Lebanon's affairs, and other senior officials in order to
coordinate their joint positions ahead of the meeting with
Annan, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Israel has offered to withdraw its troops from south Lebanon
on the condition that the Lebanese government agrees to provide
security guarantees for its northern border before its pullout.
</P>
<P>
Both Lebanon and Syria flatly rejected the offer, insisting
that the withdrawal must be unconditional.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which has 40,000 troops in Lebanon, seeks a
comprehensive deal that would also involve an Israeli withdrawal
from the Golan Heights, captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East
war.
</P>
<P>
Annan welcomed the Israeli offer and has established a
committee to address the issue.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its northern
areas from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
