<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi's Cross-Border Trade Booming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 10 (Xinhua) -- A recent study shows that there is
a considerable development of trans-border trade between Malawi
and its neighbors, according to Sunday Mail.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian newspaper quoted the study by the University of
Malawi as saying that the informal cross-border trade between the
neighboring countries in the region is an important economic
activity and in some cases, the informal trade is several times
higher than the formal trade.
</P>
<P>
Malawi-Zambia informal trade monitored from the eastern border
town of Mchinji of Malawi shows that from 1995 to 1996 Malawi
exported to Zambia non-agricultural commodities worth 2.6 million
U.S. dollars, while agricultural commodites amounted to 732,000
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The main agricultural goods exported by Malawi were maize
products, Irish potatoes and beans. Malawi imported large
quantities of fertilizer and secondhand goods worth 17.2 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Malawi-Mozambique informal trade was monitored from four
border towns in the west and one in the east. Malawi exported a
total of 3.8 million dollars worth of various products, while it
imported 13.6 million dollars mainly in food products over the
two years.
</P>
<P>
Informal cross-border trade with Tanzania was monitored at the
northern border town of Karonga. Malawi exported 11.2 million
dollars worth of products, while imports were 10.8 million
dollars, mainly used clothes, electrical appliances and
kitchenware.
</P>
<P>
Malawi's total value of formal trade with the neighbors was
about 64 percent of the total informal trade, according to the
study.
</P>
<P>
The study suggests that by encouraging the cross-border trade,
Malawi can cover its annual food shortages of 250,000 to 500,000
tons without diverting its scarce national resources to importing
these commodities from outside the region at higher prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
