<HEADLINE> Iran Summons German Ambassador over Attack in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran summoned German ambassador in
Tehran Horst Baechmann on Sunday to strongly protest against the
"irresponsible act" of the German police in connection with an
attack on Iranian mourners in the German city of Cologne.
</P>
<P>
According to the Iranian official news agency IRNA, the
Iranian Foreign Ministry called for arrest and punishment of
those "who violated the religious sanctities" of Muslims and
the Iranians residing in Germany.
</P>
<P>
A group of Iranian dissidents insulted and attacked the Ashura
mourning ceremony held by Iranians and Muslims residing in Germany
to mark the death anniversary of the Shiite third Imam
Hussein. Two Iranians were injured in the clashes and sent to
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry Director General in charge of Western
Europe affairs Ali Ahani told Baechmann that the failure of the
German police to provide security for those attending the
religious rituals is not at all acceptable.
</P>
<P>
He said that the ceremony had been held with the prior
knowledge of the German officials concerned, adding that the
German government is responsible for consequences of any similar
incidents in the future.
</P>
<P>
Baechmann denounced the attack, saying that according to
reports received from the German Foreign Ministry, the
demonstration by the Iranian "counterrevolutionary agents" took
place "suddenly."
</P>
<P>
He explained that the local police in Cologne were unaware of
the significance of Ashura ceremony for Muslims, nor did they have
a precise evaluation of the sensitivity of the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
