<HEADLINE> Philippine President Told All Ready for Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing Philippine President Fidel
Ramos was told here Sunday by chiefs of the Commission on
Election, the armed forces and the national police that everything
had been ready for Monday's elections.
</P>
<P>
During a breakfast meeting of presidential and vice
presidential candidates and other concerned parties hosted by
Ramos, Commission on Elections chairman Bernardo Pardo announced
that all preparations for the national and local elections have
been done.
</P>
<P>
There will be "no postponement or failure of elections, as well
as other wrong and baseless predictions," Pardo told the
president.
</P>
<P>
"All preparations have been done to make sure that every aspect
and stage of the electoral process is carefully implemented," he
added.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the holding of honest, orderly and peaceful
elections, the poll body has also accredited three citizens'
monitoring groups to check fraud and cheating in the elections.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Staff General Mariano Clemente of the armed forces and
chief director Santiago Alino of the Philippine National Police
told Ramos that plans have been made during and after the polls in
keeping with Ramos' order for the holding of honest, orderly and
peaceful elections.
</P>
<P>
The plans include providing security to polling places,
election inspectors and Commission on Election personnel
performing election duties, protect voters from harassment,
coercion, intimidation and reprisal and continue enforcing orders
of the Commission on Elections in political subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine National Police had also identified 425 towns
and municipalities as "election areas of concerns." About 116,000
military men and policemen had been deployed all over the country
to maintain peace and order.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that as of Sunday, 33 people had been killed in
election-related violence. 
</P>
