<HEADLINE> Iran Protests to Germany for Attack on Mourners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Sunday lodged a strong
protest to the German government for the attack on Iranian
mourners in Cologne and the "irresponsible attitude" of the
German police in connection with the attack.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA quoted a statement
from the Foreign Ministry Information and Press Department as
saying that the attack took place at a time when a group
of Iranians and Muslims residing in Germany were holding
mourning ceremonies for the third Imam Hussein of the Shiite
Muslims.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry called on the German government to
arrest those involved in the incident for their "disregard of
the religious sanctities of Muslims."
</P>
<P>
Local English Daily Iran news reported that a group of
unidentified Iranian dissidents insulted Imam Hussein and the
household of the Islamic Prophet Mohammad in front of the "Iran
House" in Cologne, where Iranians mourned on occasion of Ashura,
the anniversary of Hussein's death on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian dissidents also physically attacked the mourners,
the daily said, but German police prevented the mourners from
responding to the attacks and as a result two Iranians were
injured in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
The group also surrounded the automobile carrying an Iranian
cleric "in full view of German police," spitting at the car and
shouting anti-religious slogans, it said, but they were pulled
back by a few Iranian mourners.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another report said that two Iranian dissidents
also raided a symposium in Vienna, Austria on Thursday when the
Iranian deputy foreign minister for education and research
affairs Gholamali Khoshrou delivered a speech.
</P>
<P>
The attackers threw eggs and colorful materials at the
gathering and then fled from the scene, the report said.
</P>
