<HEADLINE> 8 Arrested in Amman for Car Explosion, Bomb Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian police have arrested eight
people for a series of bomb attacks and car explosion that
happened here in the past month, Acting Information Minister Nasir
Lawzi said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Lawzi said the eight suspects,
seven Jordanians and one non-Jordanian with Arab nationality, were
caught in tandem during the past two weeks and interrogation is
underway, said Lawzi.
</P>
<P>
The acting minister said that the suspects were from the same
group with Islamist affiliation and aimed to destabilize the
country, but he declined to name the group.
</P>
<P>
Jordan will not accuse any other country at this time for the
violence, he added.
</P>
<P>
On April 30, a Volvo car exploded at the parking lot of the
Jerusalem International Hotel at the suburb of Amman, seriously
damaging itself and four other nearby vehicles.
</P>
<P>
A previously unknown group, Abu Thar Al Ghafari, claimed the
responsibility for the explosion in a statement issued in Lebanese
capital Beirut.
</P>
<P>
But the Jordanian government doubted it for lacking accuracy.
</P>
<P>
The car explosion at the hotel followed a series of bombings in
the past month that targeted the car of former head of the General
Intelligence Department Mohammad Rasoul Kilani and the car of
former Interior Minister Jawdat Sboul, as well as the residence of
Major General Yousef Gassous of the Jordanian Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
None of the explosions or attacks resulted in loss of life or
injury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
