<HEADLINE> Nigerian State Probes Ghost Worker Frauds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 10 (Xinhua) -- The government of Osun State in
southwestern Nigeria has started investigations into ghost worker
frauds involving some of the state ministries and top government
officials, media reports said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the state's Property and Funds Investigation and
Recovery Panel is now probing into a ghost worker fraud in the
Osun State Mass Education Agency.
</P>
<P>
The panel suspects that about 62 million Naira (about 730,000
U.S. dollars) were paid to ghost workers by the agency.
</P>
<P>
As part of its "war on ghost workers", the state government
suspended four directors of various agencies and redeployed seven
others in October 1996, following the discovery of alleged
misappropriation by the state's pay-at-sight committee.
</P>
<P>
Among the agencies and ministries where misappropriation were
discovered are the office of the military administrator,
ministries of agriculture, information, works and transport and
the state Hospital Management Board.
</P>
<P>
They will all be investigated by the panel, the reports said.
