<HEADLINE> India's Healthcare Facilities Fragile: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 10 (Xinhua) -- India has only one doctor for
about every 2,500 people showing the weak and fragile healthcare
infrastructure, Press Trust of India (PTI) quoted a latest study
as saying here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We have 407 doctors, 214 nurses and 1,600 beds for every one
million people in a population of 950 million," the study said.
</P>
<P>
Infant mortality in India is among the highest as an average of
80 out of every 1,000 children born die, while 39 in a developing
country like Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Life expectancy of 55.5 is also among the lowest, it said,
adding it is 66.5 in Thailand and 59 in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
With the population growing at 2.5 percent, India would be a
country of one billion people by the turn of the century. To
fulfill the healthcare needs, India would need to add a whopping
80,000 beds annually for the next five years, the study added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
