<HEADLINE> Hotel Galadari in Colombo Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 10 (Xinhua) -- The Galadari Hotel, a five-star
hotel in Colombo, has reopened for business after six months of
closure due to extensive damages by Tamil rebels' suicide bomb
explosion last October.
</P>
<P>
Hotel general manager Chandra Mohotti said Sunday that the
500-room luxury hotel's restaurant and the public areas were
reopened to the public Saturday along with 120 rooms.
</P>
<P>
The estimated damages suffered by the hotel which is owned by
Galadari brothers of Dubai with a fully Sri Lankan management, ran
into 13 million U.S. dollars and state loans worth 5.7 million
U.S. dollars were granted for the repair work, Mohotti said.
</P>
<P>
The bomb, which targeted the nearby Twin-Tower World Trade
Center killed 10 of the hotel's staff and caused slight injuries
to a few number of foreign visitors, he added.
</P>
<P>
A Tamil rebel powerful truck-bomb exploded in the hotel on
October 15, 1997, killing more than 10 people and injuring over
100 others. 
</P>
