<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Export Franchise City Concept to Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 10 (Xinhua) -- A Malaysian company which
introduced the "franchise city" concept is seeking to export the
idea to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Kota Francais (M) Sdn Bhd signed here Sunday a memorandum of
understanding with Jetpa Holdings of Turkey to jointly develop the
concept in Turkey and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
The concept involves the siting of businesses with franchise
capabilities under one roof.
</P>
<P>
Kota Francais and Jetpa Holdings which are involved in Turkey's
construction, motor, tourism, food, electronics and education
sectors, were represented at the signing by Chief Executive
Officer Zainal Ariffin Osman and Chairman M. Fadil Akgunduz
respectively.
</P>
<P>
"We have about six months to finalize the details. Maybe next
year, we can start something in Turkey," Zainal told reporters
after the signing.
</P>
<P>
Kota Francais's first franchise city in Shah Alam near Kuala
Lumpur would be operational in September, and has so far attracted
a tenancy rate of 60 to 70 percent, Zainal said, adding his
company was in the midst of establishing more franchise cities
within Malaysia, including in the states of Perak, Kedah,
Terengganu, Johor and along the peninsula's east coast.
</P>
<P>
He said Kota Francais hoped to establish 25 franchise cities
throughout the country by the year 2005 at a total cost of 2.5
billion ringgit (about 659.63 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
