<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Philippine Polls, a Fight Between </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Is it popularity or political
machinery that counts in Philippine politics and finally gains the
upper hand in the presidential race on Monday, when some 34
million Filipino voters go to the polls to choose their country's
next president?
</P>
<P>
With 10 official presidential candidates set to reach the
election day, Monday's presidential race will be the largest and,
most likely, one of the tightest in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
Based on the results of various opinion polls conducted in the
run-up to the elections, many pundits predicted a virtually
two-way fight between highly popular Vice President Joseph Estrada
of the main opposition, and Speaker of the House of
Representatives Jose de Venecia of the powerful ruling party.
</P>
<P>
In the latest poll conducted on May 2-4 by the country's most
respected pollster, the Social Weather Station (SWS), Estrada, the
standard-bearer of the LAMMP (Fight of Patriotic Filipino Masses)
party, solidified his massive lead with a hefty 33 percent support
rating.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia of the ruling Lakas-NUCD (National Union of
Christian Democrats) party emerged as Estrada's closest rival with
15 percent, the best showing for the veteran politician who has
fared poorly in many previous polls.
</P>
<P>
The poll also found three candidates crowding for the third
place -- Senator Raul Rocco, former Cebu governor Emilio Osmena,
each with 11 percent, and former Manila mayor Alfredo Lim at 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who made a household name in the 1960s by playing
Robin Hood-style heroes fighting for the poor, has led all opinion
polls conducted this year by the SWS, which almost accurately
predicted the results of the 1992 presidential ballots.
</P>
<P>
Estrada, who runs on a populist pro-poor platform, enjoys a
broad constituency among the ordinary masses which account for
more than two-thirds of the country's 70 million population.
</P>
<P>
He vows to drastically reduce the 35-percent national poverty
rate, give priority to agriculture and education, and restore
peace and order in the country.
</P>
<P>
"My obvious edge is that among all the candidates, I'm
identified with the poor," said the portly and mustached ex-movie
star, a college dropout who is disliked by the business community
and the Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
Confident that the presidency was already in his bag, Estrada
on Thursday announced some of his cabinet choices and the
priorities in the first 100 days of his administration.
</P>
<P>
Estrada even claimed victory at a rally held Friday. "It's all
over but the counting," he said. "I think I will win because all
the surveys show I am leading."
</P>
<P>
But political analysts say that Estrada's victory is still not
a foregone conclusion although the polls did show a trend in favor
of him and Filipino voters are usually prone to choose
personalities over parties and issues.
</P>
<P>
With the support of incumbent President Fidel Ramos which means
powerful political machinery and sufficient resources, De Venecia
still stands a big chance to win the election despite his low
popularity, they add.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia has been lackluster in many previous opinion polls
until the latest SWS survey, dogged by his acknowledged image as a
"trapo" (Filipino parlance for the traditional politician good at
backroom deals).
</P>
<P>
The endorsement of Ramos, who picked De Venecia as his
successor and remains a popular figure, is expected to bring one
to two million votes for De Venecia. Ramos, who must step down on
June 30 when his single six-year term ends, is barred by the
constitution to run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
But the most important advantage of De Venecia is his
formidable political machine which will play a major role in
winning actual votes on the election day, according to columnist
Alex Magno.
</P>
<P>
Magno said that a strong and complete slate, including many
unopposed candidates, in both congressional and local elections
showed the Lakas-NUCD has a clear organizational superiority over
the other competing parties, including Estrada's LAMMP.
</P>
<P>
"The Lakas has the clear advantage due to the party's
100-percent candidate presence in the 17,000 elective posts open
in this election," he said. "The closest organizational rival, the
LAMMP, has only 30-percent candidate presence. This is going to
tell in the final vote."
</P>
<P>
According to Magno, the Lakas-NUCD's organizational superiority
may bring a lot of machine votes for De Venecia since its local
candidates will draw their followers to vote for him and win "soft
votes" from rival candidates.
</P>
<P>
Soft votes refer to voters who have low-level conviction about
their initial preferences. According to the estimate of the De
Venecia camp, a lot of the lower-income Estrada voters are soft.
</P>
<P>
In fact, De Venecia himself did not hesitate to declare that he
is "the man to beat" due to his powerful political machine.
According to him, the Lakas-NUCD has a membership of 6.5 million
which means millions of command votes.
</P>
<P>
Being speaker of the lower house for six years, De Venecia also
boasts support from most provincial governors and other local
officials, as well as from several influential religious groups
which usually demand their followers vote as a bloc.
</P>
<P>
But some analysts said there are also chances a dark horse
emerges in the May 11 polls, since no one is expected to get major
support in a field of as many as 10 contenders.
</P>
<P>
Under the election law, the presidential candidate who gets the
highest number of the votes will be declared the winner. No
run-off will be held.
</P>
<P>
Some voters, particularly those who loathe both the
controversial Estrada and the "trapo" De Venecia, may turn to
other candidates with a better image, thus creating some
imponderables.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the analysts say, it is still too early to rule out
the possibility that Rocco, a famed lawyer, or Lim, a tough
crimebuster who has the backing of former president Corazon
Aquino, might land Malacanang, the country's presidential palace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improving Vegetables with New Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 10 (Xinhua) -- More varieties of vegetables will
be served by Chinese families because of new technology.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xiaobing, an official with the Ministry of Agriculture,
said the Chinese government is making efforts to please Chinese
housewives by filling their vegetable baskets through the use of
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
"The well-to-do Chinese families not only need a sufficient
supply of vegetables, but also hope to taste what vegetables
should be," he said.
</P>
<P>
Modern science and technology have not only helped increase
the vegetable output in China, but spoiled their tastes partly due
to the use of fertilizers, said Chai Min, a staff member with the
China Vegetable Seed-Breeding Center.
</P>
<P>
So the government also needs to turn to science and technology
to make Chinese food taste better and more delicious, he added.
</P>
<P>
Wang noted that both rural and urban vegetable markets are now
steadily priced and sufficiently supplied, though Chinese families
are demanding more vegetables to meet their tastes.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that China has made some progress in this
field during the past few years. North China's Shanxi Province has
spread 138 types of vegetable seeds during the past five
years. Liaoning Province in the northeast and Qinghai Province in
northwest of China have also made progress in reducing fertilizer
use on vegetables, he added.
</P>
<P>
"China will also conduct a study on seed-breeding, and
increasing nutrition of vegetables soon," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
To make Chinese vegetables safer for consumers, the Ministry of
Agriculture will pass a regulation guiding the production and
technological process of vegetables this year, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
