<HEADLINE> 10,000-Year Old Animal Fossils Found in Dalian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, May 10 (Xinhua) -- A large number of animal fossils
dating back to the late Quaternary Period (about 10,000 years ago)
have been found near this port city in northeast China's Liaoning
Province.
</P>
<P>
The fossils are now stored in the Jinzhou Museum in the city of
Dalian.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Mingcheng, the curator of the museum, the
fossils were disovered in a limestone cave on the northeast slope
of Mount Taishan in the suburbs of the city. He explained that
they include bones and teeth of cattle, sheep, deer, and hairy
rhinoceroses.
</P>
<P>
Local geologist Liu Jinyuan said that a severe flood probably
carried the remains into the cave, which is even older than the
fossils.
</P>
<P>
"The fossils will provide valuable clues for the study and
research on the area's ancient animal groups and geological
conditions," Liu added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
