<HEADLINE> 1,900-Year-Old Puppets Found in Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Two 1,900-year-old puppets have been
found in an ancient tomb in Fufeng County in northwest China's
Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
One of the puppets is 13 cm tall and has a body made of red
pottery. The head is missing, and is thought to have been made of
wood, and therefore rotted away, according to Luo Xizhang, curator
of the Shaanxi Zhouyuan Museum.
</P>
<P>
The puppet is in a kneeling position. If a string attached to
its head was pulled, the puppet could be made to Kowtow, Luo said.
</P>
<P>
The other puppet, 11 cm tall, is in a sitting posture. It is
thought that its missing right hand held a fan and was moveable.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa Urged to Recycle Solid Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 10 (Xinhua) -- With waste disposal being a major
threat to the environment in southern Africa, environmentalists
have repeatedly urged countries in the region to recycle waste
materials to ease pollution.
</P>
<P>
Recycling is the separating and processing of waste materials
into reusable materials. The recycled product, which may or may
not be similar to the new unrecycled material, is used again.
Other than easing pollution, recycling also reduces raw material
production costs, the Sunday Mail reported.
</P>
<P>
Managing director of a South African-based company Sappi Waste
Paper Dennis Skeate told the paper that huge piles of waste have
been seen across the region's dump sites and could harbor
diseases and pests and pollute land, air and water.
</P>
<P>
Public concern with environmental quality has made recycling a
major growth industry in Europe. But of all southern African
countries, only South Africa is so far increasing economic gains
in the recycling since it has the technology and other countries
rely on her for recycling, he said.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, recycling has helped create employment and
provides a source of income for people on the streets who sell
waste materials to recyclers.
</P>
<P>
According to a South African environmental researcher Ntombi
Silomntu, "Developments that are taking place in the tyre and
cement industries on how to tackle the problem of scrap tyres are
quite impressive. Old tyres are used as road asphalt, and there
are plastic and glass recyclers too."
</P>
<P>
In Namibia, recycling as a waste reduction option is a fairly
new concept. But only plastic is recycled in Namibia and most
items that need recycling, for example, glass and paper are
transported to South Africa and reimported to be made into
different secondary products.
</P>
<P>
Most countries in southern Africa recycle waste paper, very
few recycle waste beverage cans or soft drink cans and other tin
products on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has a 20 percent recovery rate with a minimum of five
to eight tons of used beverage cans being recovered every month.
However, the cans are transported to South Africa for recycling.
In Zimbabwe, only plastics and paper are recycled locally.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, the collection of recyclable waste such as
vehicle bodies, empty oil drums, tins and others, help to reduce
the rate of filling of the Tabata dumping site in Dar es Salaam,
the paper reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
