<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Will Filipinos See Peaceful Elections? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Will the Filipinos see a "clean,
peaceful and orderly election" on Monday when they go to the polls
to elect the country's president, vice president and
parliamentarians as well as local officials?
</P>
<P>
Will a possible failure of elections in parts of the country
become a reality? What will happen if the elections fail in some
places?
</P>
<P>
These questions have been hitting the headlines of newspapers
and television programs in the Philippines since the election
campaign started three months ago.
</P>
<P>
There have been widespread concerns that Monday's national and
local elections could be marred by vote-rigging, which could spark
violence as were the cases with the previous elections.
</P>
<P>
In the 1992 general elections, which were regarded as
relatively orderly, more than 100 people were killed in
election-related violence.
</P>
<P>
This year, the situation has improved as compared with the
previous ones, yet 33 people have reportedly been killed in
election-related violence since January.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said that election-related violence could
escalate if large-scale ballot-rigging takes place.
</P>
<P>
Watchdog groups in the country are charging that the Commission
on Elections, which overseas the elections, has not taken measures
to prevent possible large-scale vote-rigging by parties and
candidates, which they said would spark more violence.
</P>
<P>
They said the commission had not barred hundreds of officials
suspected of cheating during the 1995 Senate elections from
helping to count this year's votes.
</P>
<P>
Retired Supreme Court justice Teodoro Padilla, who headed the
tribunal on the Senate polls in 1995, has warned recently that
Monday's elections could even be worse in the matter of cheating
compared with the 1995 elections.
</P>
<P>
His warning was echoed by Manolo Gorospe, chairman of the
election commission who said in a statement two weeks ago that the
commission is expecting a failure of elections in many parts of
the country, particularly in Mindanao, the most violence-prone
region.
</P>
<P>
Such a failure may lead to a delay in the proclamation of
national and local leaders, including the president, he said.
</P>
<P>
Former Senate president Jovito Salonga has also warned that if
there was no proclamation on or before June 30, the day President
Fidel Ramos' six-year term ends, there would be "a big problem,
chaos and a vacuum in the leadership."
</P>
<P>
In this case, the military could take over because it is the
"strongest entity" that can move in, he said, citing the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
If this really happens, there would be political chaos in the
country, analysts said, adding that the opposition will revolt
against a military take-over.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Jose Estrada, who leads the field of 10
presidential candidates, said: "If I'm cheated out of victory, I
will go to hills and fight."
</P>
<P>
Former president Corazon Aquino has also said that if the
elections are rigged, she would lead another "people power"
movement which led to the fall of her predecessor Ferdinand Marcos
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, rebel groups in the country have threatened to make
troubles during the elections. The Moro Islamic Liberation Front
and other rebel groups have threatened to disrupt the elections if
polling is conducted as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
However, Ramos, who is limited to a single six-year term by the
constitution, has assured the Filipinos that there will be no
failure of elections this year, and that he will step down on June
30.
</P>
<P>
He said the armed forces and the police, which have been
deployed in all violence-prone areas in the country, will do
whatever they can to deal with the trouble makers.
</P>
<P>
Some Presidential and vice presidential candidates, invited by
Ramos as a final pre-poll step to ensure a "clean, peaceful and
orderly" election on Monday, attended a breakfast meeting Sunday
at the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
The meeting could serve "a forum for the exchange of views to
promote open and transparent elections," the Presidential Office
said.
</P>
<P>
On May 2, all the front runners in the presidential race signed
a covenant promising to play their part in ensuring peaceful,
honest, and orderly elections.
</P>
<P>
These indications point to relatively orderly elections in the
country this year.
</P>
<P>
But political analysts say election uncertainties in the
Philippines will not come to an end until the election results are
accepted by political parties and a new government is formed in
seven weeks after the polls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
