<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Textile Industry in New Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's textile industry is
facing another viability crisis, with thousands of jobs now on
the line due to the current high prices of local lint despite
marked falls on the world market.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe Textile Workers' Union has appealed to the
government to urgently take action to save the troubled textile
industry following reports that several big companies were on the
brink of closure due to unfair pricing policies, the Sunday Mail
reported.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the Union Simon Tsokotsa told the paper
that most ginneries which acted as middlemen between growers and
spinners had not reduced their lint selling prices despite marked
falls on the world market, resulting in local spinners buying
lint at unfairly higher prices than other spinners worldwide.
</P>
<P>
If the trend was allowed to continue, he said, local companies
would be unable to compete internationally due to viability
problems, forcing widespread closures and loss of thousands of
jobs.
</P>
<P>
Tsokotsa called for the urgent formation of a task force to
review the downwards of the selling price of cotton lint to
spinners to save them from collapsing.
</P>
<P>
Since the introduction of economic reforms in 1991, the
textile industry has faced many obstacles which resulted in
several companies closing down, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jobs have decreased from 20,000 in 1990 to 13,000 presently, a
decrease of about 35 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
The union predicted that by the end of the year, 4,000 more
jobs could be lost if the situation did not improve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
