<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Gold Market Suffers Great Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's gold market suffered a loss
of 145 million Jordanian dinars (about 205 million U.S. dollars)
within the past six months due to the drop of gold prices at the
international market, semi-official Jordan Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We in the kingdom have 70 tonnes of gold worth 600 million
dinars (about 847 million dollars) (six months before). At the
current prices, the gold is worth about 455 million dinars (about
642 million dollars)," the paper quoted Ghaleb Sakijjha, secretary
of the Jewellers Association, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Due to the excessive supply of gold at the international
market, world gold prices dropped at the end of last year and
the beginning of 1998, thus affecting local demand for gold
and causing a stagnation in Jordan's gold market, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
