<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Media Urged to Cover Constitutional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's National Constitutional
Assembly (NCA) has urged the media to play a leading role in
publicizing the on-going debate on constitutional reforms so that
ordinary Zimbabweans understand the need for a new constitution.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a two-day workshop Saturday on the media and the
constitution in Bulawayo, the country's second largest city, NCA
national coordinator Isaac Maphosa said the whole process would
die a natural death if it did not receive publicity, the Zimbabwe
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabweans would have missed an opportunity to participate in
deciding their destiny, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is a craving nation out there waiting for information
so that they can digest it and make an input into the
constitutional debate," he said.
</P>
<P>
The present constitution, drafted at Lancaster House, London
in 1979, was a compromise document reached between the then
Rhodesian Prime Minister Ian Smith, Abel Muzorewa's United
African Nation Council, the Patriotic Front coalition of Robert
Mugabe's Zimbabwe African National Union (ZANU) and Joshua
Nkomo's Zimbabwe African People's Union (ZAPU) to end the second
Chimurenga war.
</P>
<P>
Debate to reform the current constitution was now gathering
momentum with the launch of the NCA, an organisation comprising
labour unions, civil society and churches.
</P>
<P>
Maphosa said the NCA was trying to bring in the entire
spectrum of society to decide their destiny through participation
in a constitutional reform debate in order to come up with a
constitution they could call their own.
</P>
<P>
In the recent debates, the trade union and opposition parties
and some ruling ZANU-PF members and parliament members demanded
constitutional reforms to limit presidential terms and urge
current President Robert Mugabe to retire.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe has been the country's leader since independence in
1980. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
