<HEADLINE> Kenya to Privatize Tea Authority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 10 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Tea Development
Authority (KTDA) will be privatized by 2000 following a long-term
dispute with local tea farmers.
</P>
<P>
The body will become a private company owned by farmers under
the name Kenya Tea Development Agency, said KTDA Managing
Director Eustace Karanja Saturday.
</P>
<P>
An association of small-scale tea factories and growers will
soon be formed to promote and foster the development of the
industry in small-holder areas, he was quoted by Sunday Nation
newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The new company, an association of small-scale tea growers,
will be incorporated in January 2000, and elections of directors
to be held in 2001, he said.
</P>
<P>
It will also issue guidelines on tea cultivation standards and
requirements, tea manufacturing and packaging standards,
transportation and housing.
</P>
<P>
The existing loan guarantees of factories, he said, will not
be affected by the move, though all KTDA assets will be
mortgaged.
</P>
<P>
The KTDA now owes the government more than 1.8 billion
Shillings (30 million US Dollars) and has guaranteed 2.5 million
Shillings (41,700 US Dollars) in loans to various tea factories.
</P>
<P>
The Authority has been severely criticized by farmers and
boycotted for several times in the last few years. Some farmers
had called for its abolition, arguing it did not serve their
interests.
</P>
<P>
Last December, small-scale farmers demanded that they be
de-linked from the KTDA, claiming the body had outlived its
usefulness.
</P>
<P>
The body has also been accused of failure to collect tea on
time and exploiting farmers by paying them "peanuts" for
high-quality green leaves.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 representatives of tea-growing districts said
then they wanted to run their own factories or to get more
involvement in the running of the KTDA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
