<HEADLINE> Kenya to Launch National Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is spending 2.04 billion
Shillings (34 million U.S. Dollars) on the national census set
for August next year, Planning and National Development Assistant
Minister Elijah Sumbeiywo has said.
</P>
<P>
The census, which will be the fourth since the country's
independence in 1963 and sixth since 1948, projects a population
of 30 million by next year, local press reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has committed 986 million Shillings
(16.43 million Dollars) -- half the budget -- in preparations
"well at an advanced stage," Sumbeiywo was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the money is expected to come from donors
including the U.N. Population Fund and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The census bill will certainly dent the June budget against a
backdrop of scarce resources, for which the government intends to
freeze new development projects as one of the ways to salvage the
tattered economy, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's last census was held on August 24/25, 1989. It was
steeped in controversy and the results was withheld until March
1994, putting Kenya's population at 21,443,636, including
foreigners residing in Kenya at the time.
</P>
<P>
The census ranked Kenya's eight top ethnic groups as follows:
Kikuyu - 4,455,865; Luhya - 3,083,273; Luo-2,653,932; Kalenjin -
2,458,123; Kamba - 2,448,302; Kisii - 1,318,409; Meru -
1,087,778; Mijikenda - 1,007,371.
</P>
<P>
The Nandi, Kipsigis, Marakwet, Elgeyo and Pokot were counted
under Kalenjin, the tribe where Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
is from.
</P>
<P>
Heavy criticism came after the announcement of the results
from opposition parties based along divided tribal lines. Even
Moi dismissed the results as "a waste of time and money" at the
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
