<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Determined to Combat Money Laundering: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides has stressed his government's determination to curb
money laundering and crime in general on this eastern
Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here Saturday on measures taken
by the Cypriot government to stamp out money laundering,
Kasoulides said reports in international press about the volume
of money being laundered in Cyprus are unsubstantiated.
</P>
<P>
A Ministry of Foreign Affairs publication on "Measures Taken
by the Republic of Cyprus on Preventing and Combating Money
Laundering" was presented at the conference.
</P>
<P>
According to the publication, the government of Cyprus
attaches top priority to the need for an adequate and effective
response to the crime. To this effect, it has introduced an
appropriate legal and institutional framework, promoted
enforcement capabilities, developed appropriate policies and
implemented effective measures against money laundering.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said competitive offshore centers in other countries
and Turkey try to present Cyprus as a source of money laundering
for their own reasons. "This view is rejected by assessments from
various international organizations," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Most negative reports in the foreign press base their
arguments on the fact that Cyprus has a strong offshore sector
operating on the island, Kasoulides said, pointing out that "the
existence of these companies does not automatically mean the
island is used as a money laundering center."
</P>
<P>
Rejecting allegations that a number of offshore companies
operating in the European Union have moved to Cyprus because of
the island's lax legislation on money laundering, Kasoulides said
Cyprus has adopted all relevant regulations recommended by
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has ratified the 1988 Vienna Convention and has signed
the 1990 European Convention on Money Laundering.
</P>
<P>
The amount of money laundered each year in the world's
financial system was recently estimated to exceed 500 billion
U.S. dollars. Almost 70 percent of these laundered funds are
estimated to be derived from drug trafficking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
