<HEADLINE> Philippine Military Won't Take Over if Elections Fail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Philippine armed forces chief Gen.
Clemente Mariano said Sunday that the military respects the
country's electoral system and will not take over civilian rule in
case of disturbances or unrest following possible failure of
elections.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no military takeover," Mariano said in response
to press reports that national and local elections to be held on
Monday might fail due to fraud, cheating and violence.
</P>
<P>
Civilian rule must be supreme over military rule, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that fraud and cheating had been found in the
registration of some voters in Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
In addition, 33 people have been killed in election-related
violence in the country.
</P>
<P>
To ensure honest, orderly and peaceful elections on May 11,
about 116,000 troops and policemen have been deployed all over the
country, especially in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Also on Sunday, senator Gregorio Honasan, a former army colonel
who helped topple the late ex-president Ferdinand Marcos in 1986,
said he would launch another putsch similar to what he and other
soldiers did in 1986 should the coming elections fail.
</P>
<P>
Former president Corazon Aquino has also reportedly expressed
the same idea.
</P>
<P>
At stake in the May 11 elections are president, vice president,
12 out of 24 senators, 260 House representatives, 78 provincial
governors and thousands of local officials and councilors.
</P>
</TEXT>
