<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Electoral System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Filipino voters go to the polls
Monday to elect a new president, a new vice president, 12 out of
24 senators, 260 members of the House of Representatives, and more
than 17,000 local government officials and councilors.
</P>
<P>
Under the election law, the president is elected by direct
popular vote for a single term of six years. The vice president is
elected for a six-year term in a separate election at the same
time as the president. He or she can serve a maximum of two terms.
</P>
<P>
The canvass of the votes for president and vice president is
conducted by the National Board of Canvassers composed of all
members of the bicameral Congress.
</P>
<P>
The candidates obtaining the highest number of votes for
president and for vice president shall be declared elected. The
president of the Senate, who is chairman of the National Board of
Canvassers, shall be the one to proclaim the winning candidates.
</P>
<P>
But in case two or more shall have an equal and the highest
number of votes, one of them shall be chosen as president or vice
president by a majority vote of all the members of Congress in a
joint session assembled.
</P>
<P>
All 24 Senators are directly elected for six years by national
vote. But one half of the membership of the Senate shall be
elected every three years.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's constitution adopted in 1987, there are a
maximum of 250 members of the House of Representatives. But on
Monday, there will be 260 seats of the lower house of parliament
at stake, according to a guide issued in April this year by the
Commission on Elections (Comelec).
</P>
<P>
Among the 260 representatives, 80 percent or 208 shall be
elected by district, while the remaining 20 percent or 52 shall be
elected under a party-list system which will be implemented Monday
for the first time in the country, the Comelec said.
</P>
<P>
In the previous and current legislatures, the party-list or
sectoral representatives were appointed by the president from
lists of nominees proposed by indigenous, but non-religious,
minority groups.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, voters will cast two votes for the House of
Representatives -- one for the district representative and the
other for the party the voter wants represented in the lower
chamber.
</P>
<P>
More than 120 parties which have been accredited by the Comelec
will participate in the country's first ever party-list election
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Party-list Law, the party-list system is a mechanism
of proportional representation in the election of members to the
lower house.
</P>
<P>
The system is designed to enable small political parties and
marginalized and under-represented sectors to obtain possible
representation in the lower chamber, which traditionally, is
dominated by parties with big political machinery.
</P>
<P>
Instead of individual candidates, only registered organized
groups such as the peasantry, urban poor, youth, indigenous
cultural communities and veterans can participate in the
party-list election.
</P>
<P>
A party shall submit to the Comelec a list of at least five
nominees to represent it. Once the party obtains the required
number of votes, the Comelec shall proclaim the party-list
representatives according to their rankings in the list of
nominees.
</P>
<P>
A party should obtain at least 2 percent of the total votes
cast for the party-list system nationwide in order to be allocated
one seat.
</P>
<P>
Only a maximum of three seats may be allowed per party. Seats
are allocated at the rate of one seat per 2 percent of votes
obtained.
</P>
<P>
Five major political parties, which have largest party
representation in the lower house at the start of the current
Congress, are disqualified from participating in Monday's
party-list election.
</P>
<P>
The five parties are the ruling Lakas-NUCD (Peoples'
Power-National Union of Christian Democrats), the Liberal Party
(LP), the LDP (Fight of Democratic Filipinos), the National
People's Coalition (NPC), and the KBL (New Society Movement).
</P>
<P>
Party-list representatives are entitled to the same
deliberative rights as the regular members of the lower chamber.
They shall serve for a term of three years with a maximum of three
consecutive terms.
</P>
<P>
Also up for grabs are 78 provincial governors and an equal
number of vice-governors, 81 city mayors and the same number of
city vice-mayors, 1,526 for both municipal mayors and municipal
vice-mayors, 722 provincial board members, 912 city councilors and
12,232 municipal councilors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
