<HEADLINE> Myanmar Seeks Double Taxation Avoidance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is seeking avoidance of
double taxation with more countries to improve its international
investment climate and ensure a free flow of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar reached an agreement on double taxation avoidance (DTA)
with Malaysia in March this year, the first such agreement after
it promulgated Foreign Investment Law in late 1988.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is currently holding negotiations with Singapore and
three other countries for the conclusion of DTA agreements,
according to the latest issue of a local journal -- the Golden
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
In order to facilitate future negotiations on DTA, a model
draft agreement based on the United Nations model taxation
convention between developed and developing countries is soon to
be brought out, the journal said.
</P>
<P>
At present, Myanmar provides unilaterally tax exemptions and
reductions to attract foreign investment, based principally on its
own laws.
</P>
<P>
Up to the end of April 1998, investment from 23 countries or
regions reached seven billion U.S. dollars in nearly 300 permitted
projects, of which investment from countries of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) accounts for 50 percent, according
to the latest official statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
