<HEADLINE> New President's Inaugural Speech Applauded in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, May 9 (Xinhua) -- The inaugural address of Miguel
Rodriguez, the new Costa Rican president, has received positive
reaction across the nation.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rican politicians welcomed two elements in the
address: the tone of conciliation, and the economic and social
targets set by Rodriguez, who swore in on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez committed himself in the speech to achieve an annual
economic growth of six percent, a yearly inflation of no more than
five percent, a poverty index below 17 percent and an unemployment
rate of less than five percent.
</P>
<P>
Former President Luis Alberto Monge said that Rodriguez's
speech broke with the tradition that the incoming president
criticizes the outgoing.
</P>
<P>
Luis Fishman, current president of the Legislative Assembly,
said that speech signaled a radical change in the takeover
ceremony. Leaders of the two major parties have started a
civilized power transition, he added.
</P>
<P>
Jose Maria Figueres, the outgoing president, said that the
speech clearly paved a way for the future.
</P>
<P>
Archbishop Ramon Arrieta, on his part, backed the speech
because it was a call to the unity of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, some cautious responses also surfaced amid generous
praises. A small group of political analysts regard Rodriguez's
speech as unrealistic and misleading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
