<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0500 GMT, May 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam and the United States will hold their fifth
round of negotiations on the conclusion of a bilateral trade
agreement, Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During the negotiations which will be held in the U.S. on May
18, the two sides will discuss in detail the principles governing
their economic and trade ties, covering the exchange of goods and
services, U.S. investment in Vietnam, and the issues related to
intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam and the U.S. began their first round of trade talks in
September 1996, one year after the establishment of their
diplomatic ties. (Vietnam-US-Trade Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- A senior Iranian official Saturday assured a
40-member French business delegation of Iran's preferential
policies for foreign investment, expecting more foreign capitals
to be injected into the country's ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of Iran's High Council of the Free Trade Zones
Morteza Alviri told the French delegation that foreign banks are
allowed to do business in the Iranian free trade zones and to
exchange foreign currency at floating rate being traded at free
market, according to the Iranian official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
The foreign investors doing business in the Iranian free trade
zones will enjoy a 15-year tax exemption and they are allowed to
transfer their capital and interests abroad with no limitation,
said Alviri, also presidential advisor on financial affairs.
(Iran-France-Foreign Investment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON - A major new initiative to tackle harmful tax
competition was agreed by G7 Finance Minister at a meeting here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement paves the way for more international exchange of
tax information to curb international tax evasion and avoidance
through tax havens and preferential tax regimes.
</P>
<P>
It reinforces the recommendations of the OECD Report for
curbing harmful tax competition and the complementary EU Code of
Conduct on business taxation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also commits the G7 to leading international
action on tax related crime by gathering more intelligence through
money laundering systems and providing for it to be shared
internationally by tax authorities. (UK-G7-Tax Initiative)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
