<HEADLINE> Italy to Help Landslide Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Italian Premier Romano Prodi convened
an urgent cabinet meeting on Saturday, discussing ways to help
those hit by massive landslides in southern Italy.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after the meeting, the government said it
has worked out a series of emergent measures to restore order in
the disaster-struck areas.
</P>
<P>
One of the emergent measures is to concentrate financial and
personnel strength to aid the five towns in the Campania region,
where the landslides occurred.
</P>
<P>
As its first effort, the Italian government has provided the
disaster area with a relief of 53 billion lire (about 311 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Due to week-long heavy rains in southern Italy, massive
landslides attacked five towns in the Campania region last week,
causing 119 people dead, 400 missing and more than 1,000
displaced.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the number of victims will rise sharply in
the days to come.
</P>
<P>
Officials said it is the largest landslides in the country
after World War II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
