<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Firms React Calmly to China's Ban on Direct Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 10 (Xinhua) -- International direct selling
companies have reacted calmly to the State Council's announcement
of a ban on direct sales, despite the blow to their considerable
interests in China, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
"We understand and respect the decision of the Chinese
government ... and have stopped all our activities of direct
selling," Herbert Ho, vice-president of Amway Pacific Limited, was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sunrider, a leading herbal food and skin-care cosmetic company,
is preparing a new business plan to take account of the new
regulations.
</P>
<P>
"But no matter what kind of operation we use, we will make
appropriate arrangements for the sellers," said a Sunrider
spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
Direct selling was an unknown sales style to most Chinese
before US-based Avon entered Guangzhou in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Since then, direct selling, in many cases involving pyramid
schemes, has been lauded as an opportunity to get rich quick
through introducing multiple levels of sales people.
</P>
<P>
Goods sold in this fashion, such as cosmetics and exercise
machines, can be a cash cow for sales people.
</P>
<P>
It has been estimated that at least 1,500 companies with 2.6
million employees have operated pyramid sales across the
country. Out of these, only 518 were approved by the government.
</P>
<P>
"It's necessary to stop the operation of pyramid sales since it
has begun to hurt social stability and economic development," said
Wang Zhongfu, director of the State Administration for Industry
and Commerce.
</P>
<P>
He called on the branches of his administration to help the
registered companies modify their sales mode.
</P>
<P>
According to the official ban, companies engaging in direct
selling have to wind up their business or apply to change their
licence for that of a regular retailer by October 31.
</P>
<P>
"We are in the process of working out a revised mode of
operation which will take into account the company's strong points
and the present characteristics of Chinese society," said Ho of
Amway.
</P>
<P>
The company has registered capital of around 80 million US
dollars in China and a 58,000-square-meter factory in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Nancy Ho, a spokesperson for Amway, said the government
prohibition order will not affect the company's planned investment
in Pudong New Area in Shanghai, where Amway has bought a
100,000-square-meter site to build a cosmetics plant.
</P>
<P>
Similar confidence has also been demonstrated by Avon Co.
</P>
<P>
Just a week after the announcement of the ban, Avon broke
ground for its new 40-million-US-dollar manufacturing plant in the
Taiping Industrial Development Zone in Conghua, Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
The plant will be ready in October and bring Avon's investment
in China to 90 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"We have great confidence in our long-term business prospects
in China and cooperation with the Chinese government," said James
Preston, chief executive officer and chairman of Avon Products
(Worldwide).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
