<HEADLINE> One More Hurt in Poll-Related Violence in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 10 (Xinhua) -- A woman candidate running for vice
mayor in a town in the southern Philippines escaped unhurt from an
attack Sunday, but one of her supporters was injured, police said.
</P>
<P>
The candidate was about to get off from the vehicle approaching
her house when attacked in Paracable town, Camarines Norte
province. The attacker fled, police said.
</P>
<P>
One supporter of the candidate was seriously wounded by the
shrapnel of a grenade thrown by the attacker, bringing to at least
37 the number of people injured in election-related violence.
</P>
<P>
The attack was the latest of a string of election-related
violence in the country. It was reported that a total of 33 people
have been killed in various violent incidents.
</P>
<P>
The southern Philippines is regarded as a violence-prone region
in the May 11 polls. To ensure the peaceful holding of the
elections, thousands of troops and policemen have been put on
alert in the region.
</P>
<P>
In the 1992 elections, 169 people were killed in violence.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines holds its national and local elections next
Monday. At stake are the presidency, the vice presidency, 12 out
of 24 senators, 260 members of the House of Representatives, 78
provincial governors and thousands of local officials and
councilors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
