<HEADLINE> Cambodian Refugees in Thailand Moved to News Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Some 20,000 Cambodian refugees,
mostly Khmer Rouge dependents, are being evacuated to a new camp
in the northern Thai province of Si Sa Ket for better control and
security reasons, the Bangkok Post reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said Thai military officials had begun relocating
those refugees from a makeshift camp about eight kilometers from
the border to a nearby camp.
</P>
<P>
The evacuation of the refugees, who fled the recent fighting in
Cambodia between government forces and the Khmer Rouge guerrillas,
is expected to be completed in seven days, said province governor
Poj Jaiman, who inspected the evacuation Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The evacuation is being conducted as a precautionary measure
against fears that the refugees would be vulnerable to attacks
from both Phnom Penh troops and the Khmer Rouge guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that fighting in Cambodia remained heavy
Saturday with Cambodian government forces claiming near-victory
over the Khmer Rouge which has been hit by mass defections in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Thai policemen in the province have been ordered to beef up
security at the two camps.
</P>
<P>
Also on Saturday, Thai Red Cross officials delivered 8,000 cans
of fish to refugees at the two camps as emergency relief aid.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
handed rice and canned food to the refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
