<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Threat Top Concern of Three Gorges Dam Builders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Builders of the Three Gorges Dam,
the world's largest water conservancy project, are taking measures
to fend off the threat of the summer floods and guarantee the
smooth progress of construction, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Ensuring the security of upstream and downstream cofferdams
this summer is top of our agenda," Wang Jiazhu, vice-president of
the China Yangtze Three Gorges Project Development Corp (CTGPC),
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The giant Three Gorges Project, with a total investment of
around 200 billion yuan (24.1 billion US dollars), is expected to
be completed by 2009.
</P>
<P>
The successful river closure last November opened the second
phase of the project's construction. CTGPC will build the
left-bank dam and powerhouse between 1998 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
For the last six months, the builders have been heightening and
compacting the cofferdams as well as constructing cutoff walls
inside them, said the English newspaper.
</P>
<P>
By the end of April, the area of completed cutoff walls
totalled 83,000 square meters with a maximum depth of 74 meters.
</P>
<P>
The cofferdam project is expected to be completed by the end of
May. It is capable of withstanding floods up to 72,300 cubic
meters per second, which occur only once every 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The cofferdam project is among the most difficult elements of
the Three Gorges Project. Its total earth and rock refill volume
is 10.3 million cubic meters, and the total length of the two
cofferdams is 2,438 meters, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
He said that the builders will start trial water extraction
from the foundation pit in mid June, and that all water will be
drained by the end of September.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that concrete pouring is the key element of
the second phase, and that 20 million cubic meters of concrete are
planned to be poured.
</P>
<P>
The maximum annual pouring quantity is expected to be four
million cubic meters, a new world record. But the amount this year
will only be 1.3 million cubic meters, he noted.
</P>
<P>
CTGPC has established four concrete mixing systems to produce
high-quality concrete. The company has also built a large quarry
located seven kilometers from the project site, said Wang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Government not to Reconcile with ETA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Spanish Prime Minister Jose Aznar
reiterated on Saturday that his government will not open dialogue
with the terrorist group ETA, or the Basque Homeland and Freedom.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the City of Vitoria, Aznar said "Spain will not
back down. The government will not talk with ETA."
</P>
<P>
ETA assassined a city councillor in the city of Pamplona on May
6 and a policeman in Vitoria on May 8, sparking wide-spread anger
across the country. A large number of people took to the street,
condemning the violence of ETA and Herri Batasuna, which is a
legal organization close to ETA.
</P>
<P>
As long as all the Spanish people close their ranks, Aznar
said, they can bring an end to violence, which is the best way to
wipe out terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will not give ETA and Herri Batasuna any
room for dialogue, adding that they will end up in jail.
</P>
<P>
ETA was set up in 1959 with an aim to build an independent
Basque state in northern Spain and southwestern France. It has
launched a war against the Spanish government since the 1960s,
killing about 800 people so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
