<HEADLINE> Milosevic Defies Western Pressure Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic said here Saturday that the referendum result in Serbia
last month demonstrated that it is impossible for the country to
accept any foreign meddling in the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic made the comments while meeting with U.S.
presidential envoys Richard Holbrooke and Robert Gelbard.
</P>
<P>
The Tanjug news agency quoted Milosevic as saying that
Yugoslavia hopes to develop bilateral ties and cooperation with
the United States on the basis of equality, mutual respect and
non-interference in each other's internal affairs,
</P>
<P>
However, Milosevic said his country will not be subjected to
any political pressure over the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
Although some Western countries showed an obvious partiality
toward the separatist-minded ethnic Albanian terrorists in Kosovo,
the president said, the position of the Yugoslav leadership and
people is that the issue is an internal affair of Serbia and can
only be resolved within Serbia through political means.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, a Serbian province with an ethnic Albanian majority,
has sunk into chaos since ethnic Albanians calling for
independence from Serbia clashed with the local Serb police in
February.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav and Serbian authorities have rejected any foreign
meddling or the internationalization of the issue, arguing it is
Serbia's internal affairs. 
