<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan President to Testify on Drug-Trafficking Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman
will bear witness on Tuesday to a district court in the case of a
drug trafficking plane detected by the National Police last week.
</P>
<P>
According to a judicial summons, Vice President Enrique Bolanos
and President Aleman's daughter Maria Dolores will also give
evidence during the investigation process.
</P>
<P>
As ordered by Judge Martha Quezada, the president, his daughter
and the vice president will make their statements on the case in
the presidential office, instead of in court, because they have
legal immunity.
</P>
<P>
Judge Quezada is investigating several government officials who
were allegedly involved in the crimes relating to the drug
trafficking by the Lear 35-A plane and to the forgery of official
documents.
</P>
<P>
Investigation showed that the plane, stolen from the United
States last December by drug traffickers, made at least 49 flights
since it entered Nicaragua last December without being inspected,
because it was considered the "presidential plane."
</P>
<P>
Aleman had admitted that he traveled in the plane to El
Salvador last February to attend a Central American summit, but
explained that he had not flown to any place inside the country.
</P>
<P>
Aleman had declared his innocence in the case and blamed civil
aeronautics officials, police and migration directors for the
scandal.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Nicaragua Lino Gutierrez announced Friday
that his country is willing to cooperate with Nicaraguan
authorities in the investigation of the jet case.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that President Aleman and his government will
clear what occurred here," said the diplomat.
</P>
<P>
"The United States government harbors no doubts that President
Aleman has been an untiring fighter against drug trafficking, and
that the cooperation between Nicaragua and the United States in
drug trafficking matters has been excellent," he added.
</P>
<P>
Gutierrez noted that Nicaragua seized more drugs than any other
countries in Central America, saying "I think that Nicaragua has
played a positive role in the war against drug trafficking."
</P>
</TEXT>
