<HEADLINE> Venezuela's Foreign Exchange Reserves Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's foreign exchange
reserves dropped to 14.544 billion U.S. dollars last week, the
lowest in more than a year, the central bank announced.
</P>
<P>
In the week between April 28 and May 5, the reserves fell by
117 million dollars due to a growing market demand for hard
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The drop was also attributed to less oil sales and capital
redemption as well as foreign debt repayment. The government spent
more than 600 million dollars last month servicing foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate fluctuated between 536 and 537 bolivars
against the dollar last week, still within the range allowed
by the bank.
</P>
<P>
According to official estimates, the dollar will rise to 589
bolivars by the end of the year because of the tense political
climate in the country that normally prompts a flight of capital
and a bigger demand for hard currencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
