<BODY>
<HEADLINE> General Elections to Be Held in Philippines Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Filipino voters will troop to
polling stations Monday to elect a new president,
parliamentarians, provincial governors and other local officials.
</P>
<P>
According to the Commission on Elections, which oversees the
polls, the casting of votes will start at 07:00 (GMT 23:00 Sunday)
and end at 15:00 (GMT 07:00 Monday) across the country.
</P>
<P>
There are over 34 million registered voters and 80 percent of
them are expected to turn out to cast ballots in 174,374 precincts
in the country, election officials said.
</P>
<P>
The voters will choose a new president as well as a new vice
president, 12 out of 24 senators, all 250 members of the House of
Representatives, 78 provincial governors and 1,600 mayors.
</P>
<P>
Eleven candidates from major and minor political parties are in
the presidential race to replace President Fidel Ramos, who is
barred from a second term by the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippine Constitution, the president serves a
single six-year term and is not allowed to seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
The front runners in the presidential race, according to the
latest opinion polls, are Vice President Joseph Estrada from Laban
ng Makabayang Masang Pilipino (Fight of Patriotic Filipino
Masses), Speaker Jose de Venecia from the ruling Lakas-National
Union of Christian Democrats (Lakas-NUCD), and former Manila mayor
Alfredo Lim from the Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
A poll by the Social Weather Station published last Thursday
put Estrada's support rating at 33 percent, while De Venecia
trailed in second place with 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, political analysts said the high number of candidates
means the victor will inevitably have only minority support, and a
dark horse could emerge in the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Official results of the presidential polls will not come out in
less than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
To attain a peaceful election, the government has deployed
policemen and soldiers at hundreds of "hot spots," or
violence-prone areas, in the capital city of Manila and other
regions.
</P>
<P>
Since the election campaign period started in the country in
January, at least 27 people have been killed in election-related
violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
