<HEADLINE> News Briefs From Mercosur Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, May 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are the news briefs
from the member states of Mercosur, a major regional organization
in Latin America which groups Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and
Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- More than two million Paraguayans will cast
their ballots in the country's general elections scheduled for
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The latest poll results show that Raul Cubas from the ruling
Colorado Party and Domingo Laino from the opposition Democratic
Alliance are the two most promising candidates to win the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
Cubas, 54, was named merely one month ago to replace former
general Lino Oviedo as the presidential candidate of the Colorado
Party. The latter was sentenced to 10 years in jail for an
attempted military coup in 1996.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The member states of the the Southern Cone
Common Market announced a plan here on Friday to turn their common
market into a zone free of mass-destruction weapons.
</P>
<P>
They defined the nuclear, chemical and bacteriological weapons
as well as the high-power conventional arms as being capable of
causing mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The Southern Cone Common Market, also called the Expanded
Mercosur, consists of four Mercosur member countries - Argentina,
Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay - plus Bolivia and Chile.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Mercosur countries, plus Bolivia and Chile,
expressed their support for Uruguayan Foreign Minister Didier
Opertti's candidacy to preside over the 53rd General Assembly of
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The six governments also called on other Latin American
countries to support the Uruguayan candidate.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- In 1997 alone, the Brazilian government invested 10
billion U.S. dollars in the science and technology sector,
accounting for 1.2 percent of the country's gross domestic product
(GDP) that year.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics also showed that Brazil's investments in
science and technology registered an annual increase of 14 percent
during the past five years.
</P>
<P>
In 1990, the investment was four billion dollars and 0.6
percent of the GDP, and in 1996 the figure went up to 7.9 billion
dollars and 1.1 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- At least 55 people were killed in Paraguay in
recent heavy rains caused by the "El Nino" climate phenomenon,
said a report of the country's National Emergency Committee.
</P>
<P>
The rains also forced some 85,000 persons to flee their homes
and caused an economic loss at about 70 million dollars, the
report added.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the region of Alberdi, 300 kilometers from
the capital of Asuncion, suffered most from the overflow of the
Paraguay and Parana rivers.
</P>
<P>
In another region of Chaco, the rainfall in the past two months
was some 80 centimeters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
