<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A lengthy frontpage article introduced the contributions a
missile test base affiliated to the Chinese Air Force, which is
located in a desert in northwest China, has made over the past
decades in developing the country's air force ordnance, such as
supersonic unmanned target drone and state-of-the-art air-to-air
missiles.
</P>
<P>
-- A Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman stated Saturday that
China felt shocked and indignant over the fact that some people in
Japan produced a movie to whitewash aggression and eulogize Hideki
Tojo, the top war criminal of the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the newspaper carried on its second page a
caricature along with a poem satirizing the Japanese attempt to
distort history. The cartoon shows Hideki Tojo, carrying a
skeleton face and a blood-dripping Japanese sabre, hides under a
cloak of "peace-loving hero".
</P>
<P>
-- Genetic researchers in Fudan University, one of China's
prestigious polytechnics based in Shanghai, have scored major
progress by completing the cloning of 100 human genes and
acquiring 40 new human genes with important functions.
</P>
<P>
-- Liu Minxue, an economist and member of the CPPCC National
Committee, China's top advisory body, noted that the private
sector could possibly offer more than 5 million job opportunities
each year, and urged the government to take this as a major
solution to the problem of re-employing laid-off workers from the
loss-suffering state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the CPPCC National Committee,
China's top advisory body, called Saturday for reinvigorating
Peking Opera and inheriting the cultural heritage of the Chinese
nation.
</P>
<P>
Li, also a member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee,
made this call at a Tianjin seminar in memory of Zhang Junqiu, a
Peking Opera master who died a year ago.
</P>
<P>
-- China has developed an injection form of anti-cancer
treatment based on the principles of traditional Chinese medicine.
</P>
<P>
It is said to kill cancer cells and fight metastasis while
regulating and enhancing the body's immune system.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Builders of the Three Gorges Dam, the world's largest water
control project, are taking measures to fend off the threat of the
summer floods and guarantee the smooth progress of dam
construction.
</P>
<P>
-- International direct selling companies have reacted calmly
to the State Council's announcement of a ban on direct sales,
despite the blow to their considerable interests in China.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing University, one of the top Chinese academies,
received more than 150 million yuan (18 million US dollars) in
donations from both domestic and overseas companies during its
grand centennial celebration earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
-- China Chamber of Commerce of Metals, Minerals and Chemicals
Importers and Exporters pledged itself to effect more cooperation
among coke export ventures recently so as to enhance the sector's
returns and avoid anti-dumping charges against China. 
