<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Population to Reach Eight Billion in 2025 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The world population will reach
eight billion in 2025 compared to 5.8 billion in 1997, the World
Health Organization (WHO) predicts.
</P>
<P>
Although women will be having fewer babies in 2025, an average
of 2.3 compared to 2.9 in 1995 and 5.0 in 1955, the world will
never have been so densely populated, said WHO in its World Health
Report 1998 published here Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, the population under the age of 20 will be only 32
percent of the total compared to 40 percent now.
</P>
<P>
The following are other features of life in the 21st century
outlined by WHO in its annual report:
</P>
<P>
- Every day in 1997, about 365,000 babies were born, and about
140,000 people died, giving a natural increase of about 220,000
people day;
</P>
<P>
- More people will live in cities than ever before. About 59
percent will live in urban areas and only 41 percent in rural
areas. In 1995 the ratio was 55 percent rural and 45 percent
urban. In 1955, 68 percent of the global population was rural;
</P>
<P>
- In industrialized countries, heart disease, stroke and cancer
will remain the leading causes of death. As deaths from heart
disease and stroke decline, deaths from some cancers will increase;
</P>
<P>
- In developing countries, these noncommunicable diseases will
become more prevalent, largely due to the adoption of "western"
lifestyles and their accompanying risk factors. But infectious
diseases, mainly HIV/AIDS and possibly tuberculosis, will still be
a major burden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
