<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Building First Ecological Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, May 10 (Xinhua) -- China's first ecological museum is
under construction in the southwest province of Guizhou.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that the museum, being jointly built with help
from the government of Norway, is also the first of its kind in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
The museum, located in the central part of Guizhou, is intended
to protect the folk culture of the Changjiao Miao ethnic group, a
branch of the Miao nationality.
</P>
<P>
Ecological museums are a new kind of museum which protect the
natural and cultural legacy of communities.
</P>
<P>
There are now more than 300 ecological museums worldwide, most
of them located in Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
The 4,000-strong Changjiao Miao ethnic group gets its name from
its custom of wearing head ornaments in the shape of long horns.
</P>
<P>
They live in 12 villages, and still preserve their ancient folk
customs and beliefs today.
</P>
<P>
The construction of this ecological museum was started last
June and is expected to be completed and opened to the public next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980510.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam, U.S. to Hold Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 9 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam and the United States will
hold their fifth round of negotiations on the conclusion of a
bilateral trade agreement, Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During the negotiations which will be held in the U.S. on May
18, the two sides will discuss in detail the principles governing
their economic and trade ties, covering the exchange of goods and
services, U.S. investment in Vietnam, and the issues related to
intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam and the U.S. began their first round of trade talks in
September 1996, one year after the establishment of their
diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
During the previous four rounds of talks, the U.S. side made
in-depth inquiries into Vietnam's laws and briefed the Vietnamese
side on the working mechanism of the World Trade Organization
(WTO) and the U.S. trading activities, the head of the Vietnamese
delegation, Tran Dinh Luong, was quoted by the VNA as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to Luong, the U.S. side will not grant Vietnam the
most-favored-nation trading status within the WTO framework unless
the two sides conclude a bilateral trade agreement first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
