<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Russian Street" Market to Be Moved Indoors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 10 (Xinhua) -- Every day, hundreds of foreign
tourists flock to the outdoor Yabao Road Garment Wholesale Market
here to buy cheap but quality garments specially designed for
foreigners in terms of style, pattern and size.
</P>
<P>
Within a few months, however, the market, known as "Russian
Street" because of the number of Russian and Eastern European
traders doing business there, will no longer be in the open, as
the vendors are to be moved into the brand-new Beijing Jili
Mansion, the construction of which is being funded by a Malaysian
company to the tune of 320 million yuan (38.55 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has already launched a program to
clear the streets by relocating all outdoor market places in the
urban districts to indoor venues.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, when the six-story Jili Mansion is
completed, more than 4,000 businessmen will be moved from their
outdoor stands in the 10 year-old Yabao Road market.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the Jili Mansion, with a total
floor space of 30,000 sq m, will not only accommodate the garment
wholesale market but also a three-star hotel with more than 180
rooms, and other facilities including restaurants and recreation
sites.
</P>
<P>
For the past decade the 400-m-long Yabao Road has been home to
the largest outdoor shopping area -- and the biggest retail export
center -- in the Chinese capital. It exports some one billion US
dollars-worth of garments annually, 40 percent of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
