<HEADLINE> Life Expectancy in 26 Countries to Be Above 80 Years by 2025: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- The life expectancies at birth in
Iceland, Italy, Japan and Sweden are projected to be 82 years by
2025, the highest in the world, the World Health Organization
(WHO) predicts in a report published here Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the World Health Report 1998, entitled "Life in the 21st
Century," WHO says that global life expectancy at birth, now 66
years, is projected to reach 73 years by 2025 with 26 countries
above 80 years.
</P>
<P>
Many thousands of people born at the end of the 20th century will
live throughout the 21st and see the advent of the 22nd century, WHO
says. France is projected to have 150,000 centenarians by the year
2025, compared to only 200 in 1950.
</P>
<P>
The countries with a life expectancy at birth of 81 years are
Australia, Canada, France, Greece, the Netherlands, Singapore, Spain,
and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The life expectancy will be 80 years in Austria, Belgium, Barbados,
Costa Rica, Cyprus, Finland, Germany, Ireland, Israel, Luxembourg,
Malta, New Zealand, the United Kingdom and the United States.
</P>
<P>
It will be 75 years in China, 72 years in the Russian Federation,
and 71 years in India.
</P>
<P>
The countries with the lowest life expectancies in 2025 will be
Angola, Burkina Faso, Burundi, Chad, Mozambique, Niger and Somalia (60
years); Mali and Uganda (59 years); Guinea Bissau (56 years) and
Sierra Leone (51 years). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
