<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, May 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- The remnants of the junta forces and rebel allies have
killed at least 50 people in northern Sierra Leone in a fresh
round of persecution of civilians.
</P>
<P>
The junta remnants and rebels, who were driven out of the
capital Freetown in mid-February, Friday also burnt down several
others in villages some 70 miles from Makeni, a major town in the
north of the war-ravaged country, according to a British
Broadcasting Corporation report monitored here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a local priest as saying that the people in
that area were persecuted because they firmly supported President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, who was reinstated in March after the fall of
the junta.
</P>
<P>
The remnants of the junta forces and their rebel allies then
retreated to the northern and eastern parts of the country, where
the west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) has been carrying
our an operation to mop up them. (Sierra Leone-Junta-Killings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright indicated
here Saturday she remains hopeful Israel would attend the Middle
East peace talks due to be held in Washington next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing after a Group of Eight ministerial
meeting, Albright refused to rule out the possibility of Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu attending the Washington talks.
</P>
<P>
"I have not yet taken no for an answer. I am not without hope,"
said Albright who failed to broker an agreement between Israeli
and Palestinian leaders at a London peace meeting early this week.
</P>
<P>
She noted that U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis Ross, who is in
Jerusalem, would have another meeting Saturday night with
Netanyahu in a fresh effort to keep the peace talks on track.
</P>
<P>
"I am hopeful. I think we'll have to wait and see how this
proceeds," she added. (UK-Albright-Peace Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Foreign ministers from Group of Eight (G8) countries
Saturday called on Iraq to cooperate fully with the United Nations
in order to get international sanctions against Baghdad lifted.
</P>
<P>
The final conclusions, issued at the end of the a two-day G8
foreign ministers meeting in London, said that the G8 countries
"welcome the inspections of Presidential sites carried out so far"
under the Memorandum of Understanding reached between the United
Nations and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to the full implementation of the Memorandum
of Understanding and to Iraqi compliance with its obligations"
under the UN Security Council resolutions concerned, the
conclusions said.
</P>
<P>
On Iraq's bid to get the international sanctions lifted, the
document said: "We regret Iraq's failure so far to comply with its
relevant obligations and we note that full compliance with
relevant (UN) resolutions would allow the process of lifting
sanctions to begin." (UK-G8-Iraq) 
</P>
</TEXT>
