<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More People to Enjoy Healthier, Longer Life Next Century: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 11 (Xinhua) -- Deaths before the age of 50 years
will be cut by half by the year 2025, the World Health
Organization (WHO) predicts in a report published here Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the World Health Report 1998, WHO says that global life
expectancy at birth, now 66 years, is projected to reach 73 years
by 2025.
</P>
<P>
"The most important pattern of progress now emerging in general
is an unmistakable trend towards healthier, longer life," says the
report.
</P>
<P>
However, WHO warns, in 1998 a total of 21 million people, two
out of every five worldwide, will die before reaching the age of
50 years, defined as premature deaths, including 10 million
children who will die before their fifth birthday.
</P>
<P>
"Tragically, while average life expectancy has been increasing
throughout the 20th century, three out of four people in the least
developed countries today are dying before the age of 50, the
global life expectancy figure of half a century ago," says WHO
Director-General Hiroshi Nakajima on the occasion of the
report's publication.
</P>
<P>
"Reducing these premature deaths is one of the greatest
challenges facing humanity at the dawn of the 21st century,"
Nakajima stresses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
