<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Child Care Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
released new child care guidelines Saturday and pressed Congress
to act on his child care reforms.
</P>
<P>
The president also criticized a bankruptcy reform provision
pending before Congress that would force mothers seeking child
support to compete with banks and credit card companies for
payment when fathers file for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
"That's not the law now, and if that competition starts, we all
know who will lose the contest -- the children," Clinton said in
his weekly radio address. "They shouldn't have to stand in line
for the support they need."
</P>
<P>
The weekly radio speech was dedicated to Mothers' Day Sunday
and focused on what Clinton said was government's responsibility
to help parents.
</P>
<P>
"There is no substitute for a mother's love or a parent's
responsibility. We, too, in the national and state governments,
however, have a responsibility," Clinton said. "Today and every
other day we should... do everything in our power to give our
mothers the peace of mind they deeply deserve."
</P>
<P>
The Clinton Administration issued two sets of guidelines: a
step-by-step consumer guide from the Department of Health and
Human Services for parents shopping for child care, and Justice
Department advice on screening care-givers hired to work with
children, the elderly and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines recommended include criminal checks through the
FBI's fingerprint records. Clinton has asked Congress to pass
legislation eliminating state barriers to checking criminal
backgrounds of child care workers. That plan must be approved by
Congress and all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, in his address, also promoted his 21.7-billion-dollar
package to subsidize child care for working families, the
legislation languishing in Congress, where some Republicans want
to aid stay-at-home moms and others want to use available money to
cut taxes for families instead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
